{"title_page": "2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title            = 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final\n| image            = FIFA Women's World Cup 2019 Final - US team on podium (4).jpg\n| image_size       = 250\n| caption          = The U.S. team lifts the championship trophy\n| event            = [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]]\n| team1            = [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]]\n| team1association = {{flagdeco|USA|size=30px}}\n| team1score       = 2\n| team2            = [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]]\n| team2association = {{flagdeco|NED|size=30px}}\n| team2score       = 0\n| details          =\n| date             = {{Start date|2019|7|7|df=y}}\n| stadium          = [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]]\n| city             = [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]]\n| woman_player1    = [[Megan Rapinoe]] {{nowrap|(United States)}}<ref name=\"POTM\"/>\n| referee          = [[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]] ([[French Football Federation|France]])<ref name=\"referee\"/>\n| attendance       = 57,900<ref name=\"USA-NED match report\"/>\n| weather          = Partly cloudy<br />{{convert|30|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|abbr=on}}<br />41% [[humidity]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/eng-52-0707-usa-ned-start-pdf-3044519.pdf?cloudid=rktlyniz7plxsaolhrim |title=Start list \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/match/300438259/#match-info |title=Match Facts \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n| previous         = [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2015]]\n| next             = ''2023''\n}}\nThe '''2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final''' was a [[Women's association football|football]] match which determined the winner of the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]]. It was the eighth final of the [[FIFA Women's World Cup]], a quadrennial tournament contested by the [[List of women's national association football teams|women's national teams]] of the member associations of [[FIFA]]. The match was played on 7 July 2019 at the [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]], a suburb of [[Lyon]], France.\n\nThe final was contested by the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]], the defending champion, and the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]], in their first final. The United States won 2\u20130, earning their second consecutive and fourth overall Women's World Cup title, with second-half goals scored by co-captain [[Megan Rapinoe]] from the penalty spot and [[Rose Lavelle]]. With their victory, the U.S. joined [[Germany women's national football team|Germany]] as the second team to win consecutive titles. The team's coach, [[Jill Ellis]], became the first manager to win two Women's World Cup titles.\n\nEach finalist was the reigning champion of their own respective confederation, with the United States having won the [[2018 CONCACAF Women's Championship]] and the Netherlands having won [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017]].\n\n==Venue==\n{{Further|Parc Olympique Lyonnais}}\n[[File:Parc OL.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]] hosted the final.]]\n\nThe final was held at the [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]], a suburb of [[Lyon]]. During the tournament, the stadium was referred to as the Stade de Lyon by FIFA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://img.fifa.com/image/upload/lyydkcj1chj8wwmorgbt.pdf |title=Match Schedule FIFA Women's World Cup France 2019 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=8 December 2018 |access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref> The venue has a seating capacity of 57,900, and hosted both semi-final matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/destination/stadiums/stadium/5043845/ |title=Stade de Lyon |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> The stadium was announced as the final venue when France was confirmed as host on 19 March 2015,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/La-france-organisera-la-coupe-du-monde-2019/544452 |title=La France organisera la Coupe du monde 2019! |trans-title=France will host the 2019 World Cup! |publisher=[[L'\u00c9quipe]] |date=19 March 2015 |access-date=26 June 2019 |language=French}}</ref> with the stadium officially confirmed to host the semi-finals and final in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/official-slogan-and-emblem-of-fifa-women-s-world-cup-france-2019-launc-2908450 |title=Official Slogan and Emblem of FIFA Women's World Cup France 2019 launched today |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=19 September 2017 |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref> The stadium is home venue of [[Ligue 1]] club [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]], opening in January 2016 to replace their previous stadium, the [[Stade de Gerland]].<ref>{{cite news |date=11 January 2016 |title=Lyon thump Troyes 4\u20131 at new stadium |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/sport/archives/2016/01/11/2003636933 |work=[[Taipei Times]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref> It has also hosted several [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] matches for the [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|club's women's side]], which is the most successful in European history.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 June 2019 |title=The heart of women's football: Why Lyon is the perfect city to host the World Cup |url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/06/the-heart-of-women-s-football-why-lyon-is-the-perfect-city-to-host-the-world-cup |publisher=[[Euronews]] |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=13 April 2019 |title=Record crowd watches OL thrash PSG at Groupama Stadium |url=https://www.ol.fr/en/contents/articles/2019/04/13/record-crowd-watches-ol-thrash-psg-groupama-stadium |publisher=Olympique Lyonnais |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the project for the new stadium was agreed upon by the government and commune of D\u00e9cines.<ref>{{cite news |title=Le grand stade est relanc\u00e9 |url=http://www.football365.fr/france/infos-clubs/lyon/article_270702_lyon-ol-land-Le-grand-stade-est-relance.shtml |work=France Soir |date=16 October 2008 |access-date=30 October 2009}}</ref> Stadium construction started in mid 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stadedelyonconstruction.fr/france/stadelyon/stadelyon.nsf/fr/intranet?openagent&Niveau1=Actualites&Document=045A6B5EE8A2A4BEC1257CE40030632C |title=3e trimestre 2013: c'est parti! |trans-title=Third quarter 2013: let's go! |website=stadedelyonconstruction.fr |date=30 July 2013 |access-date=26 June 2019 |language=French |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402141609/http://www.stadedelyonconstruction.fr/france/stadelyon/stadelyon.nsf/fr/intranet?openagent&Niveau1=Actualites&Document=045A6B5EE8A2A4BEC1257CE40030632C |archive-date=2 April 2015}}</ref> and finished in late 2015 at a cost of \u20ac450 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.journaldunet.com/solutions/dsi/1168948-transformation-numerique-olympique-lyonnais-stade-des-lumieres/ |title=Comment l'Olympique Lyonnais veut passer \u00e0 l'\u00e8re du stade connect\u00e9 |trans-title=How Olympique Lyonnais wants to move into the era of the connected stadium |work=Le Journal du Net |date=7 December 2015 |access-date=26 June 2019 |language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lepoint.fr/sport/football/grand-stade-de-lyon-premier-pari-gagne-pour-jean-michel-aulas-07-01-2016-2007791_1858.php |title=Grand stade de Lyon : premier pari gagn\u00e9 pour Jean-Michel Aulas |trans-title=Grand Stade de Lyon: first win for Jean-Michel Aulas |website=[[Le Point]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=7 January 2016 |access-date=27 June 2019 |language=French}}</ref> The stadium was chosen as a venue for [[UEFA Euro 2016]], where it hosted six matches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stade de Lyon |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/hosts/france/city=2156/stadium/index.html |access-date=15 September 2017 |publisher=UEFA}}</ref> The stadium also hosted the [[2017 Coupe de la Ligue Final]] and [[2018 UEFA Europa League Final]].<ref>{{cite news |date=9 December 2016 |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=2398004.html |title=Parc OL chosen to host 2018 UEFA Europa League Final |publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Coupe de la Ligue hits the road! |url=http://www.ligue1.com/coupeLigue/article/the-coupe-de-la-ligue-hits-the-road.htm |access-date=15 September 2017 |publisher=Ligue 1 |date=2 September 2016}}</ref> Outside of football, the Parc Olympique Lyonnais has hosted several musical performances,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Frisulio |first1=Elisa |title=A Lyon, Coldplay a emball\u00e9 le Parc OL |url=http://www.20minutes.fr/lyon/2083431-20170609-lyon-coldplay-emballe-parc-ol |access-date=15 September 2017 |work=20 Minutes |date=9 June 2017 |language=French}}</ref> as well as [[ice hockey]] and [[rugby union]] matches,<ref>{{cite news |title=Winter Game : bient\u00f4t du hockey sur glace au Parc OL !|trans-title=Winter Game: ice hockey coming soon at Parc OL! |url=https://www.lyonmag.com/article/78490/winter-game-bientot-du-hockey-sur-glace-au-parc-ol |access-date=4 April 2016 |publisher=Lyon Mag |date=12 February 2016}}</ref> including the [[2016 European Rugby Champions Cup Final|Rugby Champions Cup]] and [[2015\u201316 European Rugby Challenge Cup#Final|Rugby Challenge Cup]] finals of 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.epcrugby.com/news/30996.php#.WZASrXeGPow |title=Lyon to host 2016 Champions Cup and Challenge Cup finals with Edinburgh chosen for 2017 |publisher=European Professional Club Rugby |date=17 June 2015 |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref> The stadium is planned to host matches for the [[2023 Rugby World Cup]] and the men and women's football tournaments at the [[2024 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The 9 stadiums for 2023 RWC in France |url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Rugby/SouthAfrica2023/the-9-stadiums-for-2023-rwc-in-france-20171115 |access-date=7 May 2018 |publisher=Sport 24 |date=15 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stade de Lyon |url=http://www.paris2024.org/en/article/stade-de-lyon |publisher=Paris 2024 |access-date=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Jillian Ellis 2015.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|U.S. coach [[Jill Ellis]] was vying to become the first manager to win two Women's World Cup titles.]]\n\nFor the first time since [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2007]], and fifth time overall (along with [[1991 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|1991]], [[1995 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|1995]] and [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2003]]), the final featured a European team, as the continent took seven of the eight places in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ramsay |first=George |last2=Lewis |first2=Aimee |date=25 June 2019 |title=Late Netherlands penalty breaks Japan's hearts at Women's World Cup |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/football/womens-world-cup-last-16-italy-china-netherlands-japan-spt-intl/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref> The previous two finals were contested by [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]] and the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]].<ref name=\"winners\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/-676193.pdf?cloudid=e2vlheu4dbnfjyje0aoc |title=FIFA Competition winners at a glance |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref> The match was the first final since 1991 to feature a [[CONCACAF|North American]] side against a [[UEFA|European]] side.<ref name=\"winners\"/> The match was also the first final of a women's or men's World Cup to feature the defending champions against the reigning European champions.<ref name=\"UEFA\"/>\n\nThe match was a record-extending fifth Women's World Cup final for the United States, who were the defending champions and record winners of the competition with three titles. They won the inaugural final in 1991 against [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]], before winning their second title in [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|1999]] as hosts via a penalty shoot-out victory against [[China women's national football team|China PR]]. They made their next appearance in the [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2011 final]], losing on penalties to Japan, before securing their third title in the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2015]] rematch against Japan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/highlights-heroines-and-stats-from-the-first-seven-finals |title=Highlights and heroines from the first seven Finals |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=4 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> In the previous seven editions of the tournament, the U.S. never finished outside of the top three.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/womens-world-cup-2019-uswnt-wants-continue-dominant-history/hhs4yay1mqpl1xiv1fn3l3f3k |title=Women's World Cup 2019: USWNT wants to continue dominant history |website=[[Sporting News]] |date=10 June 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref> The fixture was the third consecutive appearance in the final for the United States, setting a competition record.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=548679 |title=U.S. outlasts England to reach World Cup final |publisher=ESPN |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Jill Ellis]] became the third manager to reach two Women's World Cup finals, after [[Even Pellerud]] for Norway (in 1991 and 1995) and [[Norio Sasaki]] for Japan (in 2011 and 2015), both with one win and one loss in the final.<ref name=\"statistical kit\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-milestones-and-superlatives-x6371.pdf?cloudid=i9hyrqdeoftzwuhhqw4p |title=Statistical kit, FIFA Women's World Cup France 2019: Milestones & Superlatives \u2013 Draw edition |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=11 April 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> With her counterpart [[Sarina Wiegman]], the match was the second final in which both teams have a female coach, after the 2003 matchup between [[Tina Theune]] of Germany and [[Marika Domanski-Lyfors]] of Sweden.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/ellis-wiegman-head-to-head-3044253 |title=Ellis and Wiegman: A closer look at the Final's coaches |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=6 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe match was the first Women's World Cup final for the Netherlands in their second tournament appearance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/history-beckons-in-la-grande-finale |title=History beckons in La Grande Finale |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=6 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> They were the fourth European country (after Germany, Norway and [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]]) and eighth overall to reach a Women's World Cup final, and the first new finalist since Japan in 2011.<ref name=\"winners\"/> In the Netherlands only prior tournament appearance, in [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015]], they were eliminated in the round of 16 by defending champions and eventual runners-up Japan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/fifa-women-s-world-cup-japan-scores-early-late-to-sink-dutch-1.3125237 |title=FIFA Women's World Cup: Japan scores early, late to sink Dutch |website=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=24 June 2015 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe match is the eighth meeting between the United States and the Netherlands, and the first competitive fixture as all prior matches were [[Exhibition game|friendlies]]. The sides first met in 1991, which the Netherlands won 4\u20133, but the U.S. have won all six subsequent meetings, most recently a 3\u20131 win in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2019/07/uswnt-vs-netherlands-match-history-preview-five-things-to-know |title=Five Things To Know About: Netherlands |website=[[United States Soccer Federation]] |date=6 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Route to the final==\n{{Further|2019 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#99CCFF;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | United States\n! Round\n! colspan=\"2\" | Netherlands\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#C1E0FF;\"\n| Opponents\n| Result\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group stage|Group stage]]\n| Opponents\n| Result\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|THA}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F#United States vs Thailand|13\u20130]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Match 1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|NZL}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E#New Zealand vs Netherlands|1\u20130]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|CHI}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F#United States vs Chile|3\u20130]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Match 2\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|CMR}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E#Netherlands vs Cameroon|3\u20131]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|SWE}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F#Sweden vs United States|2\u20130]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Match 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|CAN}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E#Netherlands vs Canada|2\u20131]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''[[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F|Group F]] winners'''\n<center>{{2019 FIFA Women's World Cup group tables|Group F|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=USA}}</center>\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Final standings\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''[[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E|Group E]] winners'''\n<center>{{2019 FIFA Women's World Cup group tables|Group E|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=NED}}</center>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#C1E0FF;\"\n| Opponents\n| Result\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage|Knockout stage]]\n| Opponents\n| Result\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|ESP}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Spain vs United States|2\u20131]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Round of 16\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|JPN}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Netherlands vs Japan|2\u20131]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|FRA}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#France vs United States|2\u20131]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Quarter-finals\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|ITA}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Italy vs Netherlands|2\u20130]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|ENG}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#England vs United States|2\u20131]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Semi-finals\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|SWE}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Netherlands vs Sweden|1\u20130]] {{aet}}\n|}\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Alex Morgan May19.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|[[Alex Morgan]] scored six times for the United States, including five in their opening match|alt=Footballer Alex Morgan, pictured jogging in a red U.S. uniform with the number 13.]]\n\nThe United States is the most successful team in women's football, having won three Women's World Cups in four previous final appearances and four [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic]] gold medals.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 August 2017 |title=32 years of USWNT glory |url=https://www.fifa.com/womens-football/news/32-years-of-uswnt-glory-2904417 |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kann |first=Drew |date=5 July 2019 |title=Yes, the US women's soccer team is dominant. That's because most of the world is playing catch-up |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/16/us/uswnt-dominance-womens-soccer-world-cup-history-explained/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The team had never finished below third place in all eight editions of the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Michael |date=4 July 2016 |title=On the Fourth of July, the 10 most memorable goals in US soccer history |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jul/04/usa-soccer-special-goals-fourth-of-july |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> [[Jill Ellis]] was appointed as interim head coach of the team in 2014, following the firing of [[Tom Sermanni]] between major tournaments, and oversaw qualification for the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 World Cup]] using a core inherited from earlier cycles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hays |first=Graham |date=10 June 2015 |title=Why Jill Ellis Is The Right Coach To Help U.S. Women Reclaim World Cup |url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/2015worldcup/article/13049184/how-jill-ellis-became-highest-profile-women-coach-world |publisher=ESPN W |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The United States had reached their second consecutive [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|final]] in 2015, playing in a rematch of the [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2011 final]] in which they had lost to Japan. The Americans won 5\u20132, including a first-half hat-trick by [[Carli Lloyd]], to secure their third Women's World Cup title\u2014their first since [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup|1999]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Longman |first=Jer\u00e9 |date=5 July 2015 |title=In a Rout and a Romp, U.S. Takes World Cup |page=A1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/06/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-usa-defeats-japan-to-win-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> Following an early quarter-final exit at the [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Olympics]], Ellis adjusted the team's usual formation and adopted a 4\u20133\u20133 with an emphasis on faster play under the direction of new call-ups.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=23 June 2019 |title=Jill Ellis quietly sits at the heart of U.S. juggernaut in Women's World Cup |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/23/jill-ellis-quietly-sits-heart-us-juggernaut-womens-world-cup/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=5 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup: Americans made sweeping changes to begin journey to finals |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-usa-womens-world-cup-journey-20190705-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The United States qualified for the 2019 Women's World Cup by winning the [[2018 CONCACAF Women's Championship]], outscoring their opponents 26\u20130 and defeating [[Canada women's national soccer team|Canada]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news |date=17 October 2018 |title=USA Claims 2018 CONCACAF Women's Championship Title with 2\u20130 Defeat of Regional Rival Canada |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2018/10/usa-claims-2018-concacaf-womens-championship-title-with-20-defeat-of-regional-rival-canada |publisher=U.S. Soccer |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. team, entering the tournament ranked first in the [[FIFA Women's World Rankings|FIFA World Rankings]],<ref name=\"ranking\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/ranking-table/women/rank/ranking_20190329/ |title=The FIFA Women's World Ranking: 29 March 2019 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=29 March 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707080319/https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/ranking-table/women/rank/ranking_20190329/ |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> were drawn into [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F|Group F]] and opened their title defence with a 13\u20130 victory against [[Thailand women's national football team|Thailand]], setting a new tournament record for largest margin of victory and goals in a match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Caitlin |date=11 June 2019 |title=Ruthless USA break World Cup record as they hit 13 past hapless Thailand |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/11/usa-thailand-uswnt-womens-world-cup-soccer-match-report |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> [[Alex Morgan]] scored five goals, equalling a one-match record set by compatriot [[Michelle Akers]] in 1991, and several of her teammates earned their first World Cup goals in their debuts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Anne M. |date=11 June 2019 |title=Alex Morgan has 5 goals as US routs Thailand 13\u20130 |url=https://www.apnews.com/4fedff426fff470c8d78c79ee1727373 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> The U.S. team were later criticised for [[goal celebration|celebrating]] their later goals during the match, with some media commentators and former players calling it disrespectful,<ref>{{cite news |last=Oliveira |first=Nelson |date=12 June 2019 |title=U.S. women's national team faces backlash for celebrating massive win against Thailand |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-women-national-team-criticized-for-celebrating-20190612-dv4zgqmkoff2hhywuls22jrufa-story.html |work=[[New York Daily News]] |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> but the celebrations were defended by other media commentators, the team's players and members of the opposing Thai bench.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |date=11 June 2019 |title=USWNT's Historic Rout of Thailand and the Question of Sportsmanship |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/06/11/usa-thailand-rout-celebrations-goals-jill-ellis-alex-morgan |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Guy |last2=Scott |first2=Andy |date=12 June 2019 |title=USWNT face backlash over goal celebrations in record World Cup victory |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/90minutes/ct-90mins-uswnt-face-backlash-over-goal-celebrations-in-record-world-cup-victory-20190612-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |agency=AFP |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> Ellis then fielded a squad of reserve players in a 3\u20130 win over debutants [[Chile women's national football team|Chile]], which included Carli Lloyd's pair of goals and a missed penalty kick.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keh |first=Andrew |date=16 June 2019 |title=New Faces, Same Result: U.S. Rolls Again at World Cup |page=D1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/16/sports/usa-chile-womens-world-cup.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The U.S. closed out its group by winning 2\u20130 against [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]], advancing with three [[shutout]] victories and outscoring opponents 18\u20130, a group stage record in the Women's World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keh |first=Andrew |date=20 June 2019 |title=U.S. Storms Past Sweden, Posting Third Straight World Cup Shutout |page=B9 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/20/sports/uswnt-sweden-score.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the round of 16, the U.S. played [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group B|Group B]] runners-up [[Spain women's national football team|Spain]], who conceded an early penalty in the seventh minute that was converted by captain [[Megan Rapinoe]]. Spanish forward [[Jennifer Hermoso]] found an equaliser within three minutes after capitalising on a defensive error near the top of the box, shooting from distance to beat goalkeeper [[Alyssa Naeher]] and end her shutout streak. The U.S. were awarded a second penalty kick after a foul in the box on [[Rose Lavelle]] and won the match 2\u20131 on another conversion by Rapinoe in the 75th minute per instruction from Ellis, after Morgan initially looked set to take the kick.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Steven |last2=Bogage |first2=Jacob |date=24 June 2019 |title='Winning by any means possible'; U.S. grinds past Spain to World Cup quarterfinals |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/24/uswnt-spain-world-cup/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gonzalez |first=Roger |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/uswnts-alex-morgan-explains-why-megan-rapinoe-was-the-penalty-kick-taker-and-addresses-injury-concerns/ |title=USWNT's Alex Morgan explains why Megan Rapinoe was the penalty-kick taker and addresses injury concerns |website=CBS Sports |date=24 June 2019 |access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> The Americans were then matched against hosts [[France women's national football team|France]], winners of Group A and a tournament favourite, in the quarter-finals. This was the first time the U.S. had faced the tournament hosts of the Women's World Cup.<ref name=\"UEFA\"/> Rapinoe opened the scoring in the fifth minute, with a free kick that was driven low and through several players, and added a second in the 65th minute by finishing a cut-back cross from [[Tobin Heath]] in the box. French defender [[Wendie Renard]] scored a consolation goal in the 81st minute on a headed corner kick, but the U.S. held on to win 2\u20131 and eliminate the hosts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=28 June 2019 |title=Women' World Cup recap: U.S. beats France 2\u20131 on two Megan Rapinoe goals |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-us-france-uswnt-world-cup-live-soccer-20190628-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. played [[England women's national football team|England]] in the semi-finals, but were without Rapinoe due to a hamstring injury that kept her out of the starting line-up. Her replacement, [[Christen Press]], scored the opening goal in the tenth minute on a header in the box; English forward [[Ellen White (footballer)|Ellen White]] then volleyed a shot from inside the box in the 19th minute to earn her team an equaliser. Alex Morgan restored the U.S. lead in the 31st minute, the first player in Women's World Cup history to score on her birthday,<ref>{{cite news |last=Roscher |first=Liz |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/alex-morgan-makes-history-and-gives-uswnt-the-lead-with-teasipping-birthday-goal-194734846.html |title=Alex Morgan makes history and gives USWNT the lead with tea-sipping birthday goal |website=[[Yahoo Sports]] |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> finishing a cross by [[Lindsey Horan]] with a header that she celebrated with a controversial tea-sipping gesture.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lou |first=Michelle |date=5 July 2019 |title=Alex Morgan says criticism of her tea-sipping celebration illustrates a double standard |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/07/05/sport/alex-morgan-defends-sipping-tea-trnd/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> White scored an apparent second equaliser in the 67th minute, but was ruled offside by a [[video assistant referee]] (VAR) decision. A VAR decision in the 82nd minute determined that White was fouled in the penalty area by defender [[Becky Sauerbrunn]] and awarded a penalty to England. The resulting penalty was struck by captain [[Steph Houghton]] and saved by Alyssa Naeher, the first penalty save by a U.S. goalkeeper in the Women's World Cup outside of a shoot-out,<ref>{{cite news |last=Howard |first=Chelsea |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/womens-world-cup-2019-uswnt-gives-alyssa-naeher-praise-game-changing-penalty-save/z30fzwccyprn1rk1azdi3qmb0 |title=Women's World Cup 2019: USWNT gives Alyssa Naeher praise for game-changing penalty save |website=[[Sporting News]] |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> ensuring a 2\u20131 victory for the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Louise |date=2 July 2019 |title=Alex Morgan heads USA past England into Women's World Cup final |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jul/02/usa-england-womens-world-cup-match-report |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Steven |last2=Bogage |first2=Jacob |date=2 July 2019 |title=The U.S. is in the World Cup final with a stop of penalty and a spot of tea |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/07/02/uswnt-england-world-cup/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The U.S. reached their third consecutive Women's World Cup final by winning all six matches without trailing. Their semi-final win set a new tournament record for longest winning streak with eleven wins since 2015,<ref name=\"chicago tribune\">{{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Anne M. |date=2 July 2019 |title=U.S. beats England 2\u20131 to reach 3rd straight Women's World Cup final |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/soccer/ct-world-cup-united-states-england-megan-rapinoe-20190702-zqsi5v5smjarvnxvfakf6b4kha-zqsi5v5smjarvnxvfakf6b4kha-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> as well as a record sixteen World Cup matches undefeated.<ref>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup-humble-beginnings-global-event/ |title=FIFA Women's World Cup: From humble beginnings to global event |website=[[Sportsnet]] |date=3 June 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707093510/https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup-humble-beginnings-global-event/ |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hays |first1=Graham |last2=Hamilton |first2=Tom |location=Lyon |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3890943/pressmorgan-score-to-lead-uswnt-past-england-and-into-womens-world-cup-final |title=Press, Morgan score to lead USWNT past England and into Women's World Cup final |website=ESPN |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707093729/https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3890943/pressmorgan-score-to-lead-uswnt-past-england-and-into-womens-world-cup-final |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> They scored 24 goals en route to the final, including one in the opening twelve minutes of each match, coming close to the single-tournament record of 25.<ref name=\"LAT-Coaches\">{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=6 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup final: U.S. and Netherlands coaches making history |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-usa-netherlands-world-cup-final-20190706-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=6 July 2019 |title=Dutch need to stop US from scoring early in World Cup final |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/07/06/dutch-need-to-stop-us-from-scoring-early-in-world-cup-final/39659085/ |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\n[[File:20170716 WEURO NED NOR 3522 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|Dutch winger [[Lieke Martens]] scored twice in their round of 16 victory|alt=Footballer Lieke Martens prepares to kick the ball with her outstretched left foot.]]\n\nThe Netherlands, nicknamed the Oranje, first qualified for a major women's tournament in 2009, reaching the semi-finals of their first [[UEFA European Championship]], and qualified for their first FIFA Women's World Cup in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |date=12 April 2019 |title=Wiegman: We have a dream |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/wiegman-netherlands-have-womens-world-cup-dream#sarina-wiegman-delirious-with-joy-after-winning-the-uefa-women-s-euro |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The team's rapid improvement in international competition was credited to the establishment of a [[Eredivisie (women)|professional club league]] in 2007 with investment from the [[Royal Dutch Football Association]]; the league later merged to form a [[BeNe League|combined Belgian\u2013Dutch competition]] in 2012 and split again in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=4 July 2019 |title=Netherlands looks to add Women's World Cup title to European championship |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-usa-netherlands-world-cup-final-20190704-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Eredivisie |url=https://www.knvb.com/competitions/womens-eredivisie |publisher=[[Royal Dutch Football Association]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> In the 2015 Women's World Cup, the Dutch side finished third in their group with a 1\u20131\u20131 record and advanced to the round of 16, where they lost 2\u20131 to eventual runners-up Japan.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 June 2015 |title=Mizuho Sakaguchi sends Japan to quarterfinals in win over Netherlands |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/06/24/japan-netherlands-womens-world-cup-results-mizuho-sakaguchi-goal-round-of-16 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands hosted and won the [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017|2017 European Championship]], earning their first major international title with a dominating style implemented by interim manager [[Sarina Wiegman]].<ref>{{cite news |date=6 August 2017 |title=Netherlands Women 4\u20132 Denmark Women |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40825848 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ramesh |first=Priya |date=7 August 2017 |title=Holland victory a triumph for Dutch flair and Sarina Wiegman's tactical nous |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2017/aug/07/holland-womens-football-euro-2017-sarina-wiegman |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Dutch earned the last remaining European berth in the 2019 Women's World Cup by finishing second to Norway in its [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 3|qualification group]] and winning the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA play-offs|play-offs]], defeating [[Denmark women's national football team|Denmark]] over two legs in the semi-finals and [[Switzerland women's national football team|Switzerland]] in the finals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile: The Netherlands |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/teams/team/1884883/profile/ |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=13 November 2018 |title=Dutch claim last European ticket for France 2019 |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/dutch-claim-last-european-ticket-for-france-2019 |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Dutch, ranked eighth in the FIFA World Rankings,<ref name=\"ranking\"/> were drawn into [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E|Group E]] with two of their 2015 group stage opponents, Canada and [[New Zealand women's national football team|New Zealand]], alongside [[Cameroon women's national football team|Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=8 December 2018 |title=Some familiar faces await Canada at 2019 Women's World Cup in France |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/sports-pmn/canada-to-meet-the-netherlands-new-zealand-and-cameroon-at-womens-world-cup |work=[[The National Post]] |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> Their opening match against New Zealand was scoreless until a last-minute header by substitute [[Jill Roord]] in stoppage time won it 1\u20130 for the Dutch.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pender |first=Kieran |date=11 June 2019 |title=Netherlands' Jill Roord pounces at the last to break New Zealand hearts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/11/new-zealand-netherlands-womens-world-cup-match-report |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands secured a knockout stage berth by defeating Cameroon 3\u20131 on the second matchday, with two goals by [[Vivianne Miedema]] to make her the nation's all-time top goalscorer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Poole |first=Harry |date=15 June 2019 |title=Women's World Cup: Netherlands beat Cameroon 3\u20131 to reach last 16 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48641765 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Dutch finished with a three-win record and topped the group after winning 2\u20131 against Canada. An early penalty was rescinded by the VAR and the opening goal was scored by Dutch defender [[Anouk Dekker]] in the 54th minute. [[Christine Sinclair]] scored an equaliser six minutes later, but the Netherlands restored their lead in the 75th minute through a short-range finish by substitute [[Lineth Beerensteyn]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=20 June 2019 |title=Christine Sinclair scores goal No. 182 but Canada loses to Dutch at World Cup |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2019/06/20/canada-captain-christine-sinclair-scores-goal-no-182-against-dutch-at-world-cup.html |work=[[Toronto Star]] |agency=The Canadian Press |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe round of 16 fixture for the Oranje was also a rematch against Japan, which manager Wiegman expected to end with a different result.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Jamie |date=21 June 2019 |title=Netherlands relishing Japan rematch at Women's World Cup |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/netherlands-relishing-japan-rematch-womens-world-cup/article28099375.ece |work=[[Sportstar]] |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> [[Lieke Martens]] scored in the 17th minute with a backheel flick off a corner kick, but Japanese midfielder [[Yui Hasegawa]] equalised before half-time. The second half saw Japan creating more chances, with Dutch goalkeeper [[Sari van Veenendaal]] crucially saving a shot from [[Yuka Momiki]] in the 80th minute to keep the scores level.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/finalists-keepers-in-focus |title=Finalists' keepers in focus |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=5 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> In second-half stoppage time, the Dutch were awarded a controversial penalty kick by the VAR for a handball in the box by captain [[Saki Kumagai]], which was then scored by Martens to win the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |last=McElwee |first=Molly |date=25 June 2019 |title=Japan devastated as late handball gifts Holland penalty to secure World Cup quarter-final place |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2019/06/25/holland-vs-japan-womens-world-cup-last-16-live-score-latest/ |work=The Telegraph |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands defeated [[Italy women's national football team|Italy]] 2\u20130 in the quarter-finals, also qualifying for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2020 Olympics]], through second-half headers scored by Miedema in the 70th minute and [[Stefanie van der Gragt]] ten minutes later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Begley |first=Emily |date=29 June 2019 |title=Women's World Cup: Netherlands beat Italy 2\u20130 to reach first semi-final |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48777144 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The match was played in {{convert|34|C|F}} heat and required several cooling breaks, which slowed the tempo of play.<ref>{{cite news |last=McElwee |first=Molly |date=29 June 2019 |title=Holland reach first ever Women's World Cup semi-final with two headed goals against Italy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2019/06/29/italy-vs-holland-womens-world-cup-2019-live-score-latest-updates/ |work=The Telegraph |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Netherlands reached their first Women's World Cup final by winning 1\u20130 in [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] against Sweden in the semi-finals. The match was scoreless in regulation time, due to the performances of both defences and goalkeepers, who made saves to keep several chances from breaking the deadlock. [[Jackie Groenen]] scored the lone goal of the match in the 99th minute, striking from {{convert|20|yd|m}} to beat goalkeeper [[Hedvig Lindahl]], with her first shot on target during the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |last=Edwards |first=Luke |date=3 July 2019 |title=Jackie Groenen hits extra-time winner to send Holland to World Cup final |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2019/07/03/holland-vs-sweden-womens-world-cup-semi-final-live-score-latest/ |work=The Telegraph |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=3 July 2019 |title=Judo ace Groenen throws Dutch towards unlikely World Cup glory |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/judo-ace-groenen-throws-dutch-towards-unlikely-world-001308465--sow.html |work=Yahoo Sports |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The Dutch were the third reigning European champions to reach the final, following Germany in 2003 and 2007, and the first to play a non-European country in the final.<ref name=\"UEFA\">{{cite news |date=3 July 2019 |title=Netherlands face US in Women's World Cup final |url=https://www.uefa.com/womensworldcup/news/newsid=2586627.html |work=UEFA.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands also managed to reach the final without trailing in their six victories, conceding only once in the knockout stage but not leading at half-time in any of their matches.<ref>{{cite news |date=5 July 2019 |title=The Women's World Cup is drawing record audiences |url=https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2019/07/05/the-womens-world-cup-is-drawing-record-audiences |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/82863/late-again-the-dutch-still-like-their-chances.html |title=Late again, the Dutch like their chances even if media back home don't |website=[[Soccer America]] |date=5 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the Dutch side has brought national attention to the women's football program, including thousands of fans who travelled to France to attend matches and record television ratings reaching 5 million viewers for the semi-final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Aimee |date=6 July 2019 |title=USA vs. Netherlands: Dutch World Cup success was decades in the making |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/06/football/netherlands-usa-womens-world-cup-final-spt-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lyall |first=Sarah |date=24 June 2019 |title=Painting the Town Orange: A Day Out With the Dutch at the World Cup |page=B11 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/24/sports/painting-the-town-orange-a-day-out-with-the-dutch-at-the-world-cup.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-match==\n\n===Scheduling===\nThe final's scheduling on 7 July led to a degree of criticism among supporters of women's football, as two continental men's tournament finals were held on the same day\u2014the [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica Final|Copa Am\u00e9rica]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] and the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup Final|CONCACAF Gold Cup]] in [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/a46a6df365134d8b8f8719772cbcdcc6 |title=Women's soccer: Wait and see approach to FIFA strategy |first=Anne M. |last=Peterson |agency=Associated Press |date=11 October 2018 |access-date=25 May 2019}}</ref> The latter final also featured the [[United States men's national soccer team|men's team of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |location=[[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/07/04/christian-pulisic-usa-defeat-jamaica-reach-gold-cup-final/1644682001/ |title=US defeats Jamaica to reach Gold Cup final against old foe Mexico |website=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=4 July 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> However, FIFA confirmed the Women's World Cup dates in September 2017, prior to the dates announced by [[CONMEBOL]] and [[CONCACAF]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/who-we-are/news/oc-for-fifa-competitions-approves-procedures-for-the-final-draw-of-the-2907924 |title=OC for FIFA Competitions approves procedures for the Final Draw of the 2018 FIFA World Cup |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=14 September 2017 |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhile FIFA called the scheduling a \"rare and exciting occurrence\", U.S. co-captain Megan Rapinoe criticised it as \"ridiculous and disappointing\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Blum |first=Ronald |date=4 July 2019 |title=The final insult: Women's World Cup final forced to compete with Copa America, CONCACAF |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/soccer/the-final-insult-women-compete-with-copa-america-concacaf/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> CONCACAF president [[Victor Montagliani]] said that the scheduling of the Gold Cup final had been the result of a \"clerical error\" and that the conflict was not realised until it was too late.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Rory |date=6 June 2019 |title=Women's Soccer's Big Moment, Big-Footed by Indifference and a 'Clerical Error' |page=B7 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/07/sports/womens-world-cup-preview.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Match ball===\n[[File:2019 Women's World Cup Ball.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Tricolore 19, the match ball of the final.]]\n\nThe official match ball for the final was the [[Adidas]] Tricolore 19, introduced for the knockout stage as a red-coloured variant of the Conext 19. The ball featured a blue-and-red glitch graphic, and pays homage to the original [[Adidas Tricolore]], which was introduced for the men's [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], in which France were victorious for the first time while on home soil.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/official-ball-for-france-2019-knockout-phase-unveiled |title=Official ball for France 2019 Knockout phase unveiled |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=21 June 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Officials===\n[[File:2017293155419 2017-10-20 Fussball Frauen Deutschland vs Island - Sven - 1D X MK II - 0017 - B70I0638.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|[[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]], the referee for the final.]]\n\nOn 5 July 2019, FIFA named French official [[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]] as the referee for the final.<ref name=\"referee\">{{cite news |date=6 July 2019 |title=Frappart: Final role a huge source of pride |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/frappart-final-role-a-huge-sense-of-pride |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706143910/https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/frappart-final-role-a-huge-sense-of-pride |archivedate=6 July 2019}}</ref> Frappart had been a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA referee]] since 2009,<ref>{{cite web |title=Referees: France |url=https://www.fifa.com/development/education-and-technical/referees/association=fra/index.html |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=5 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707083706/https://www.fifa.com/development/education-and-technical/referees/association=fra/index.html |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> and previously officiated at the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]], [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]] and [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017]].<ref>{{cite news |date=12 March 2018 |title=St\u00e9phanie Frappart retenue parmi les arbitres |language=French |trans-title=St\u00e9phanie Frappart among selected referees |url=https://www.eurosport.fr/football/coupe-du-monde-feminine/2019/stephanie-frappart-retenue-parmi-les-arbitres_sto7037659/story.shtml |publisher=[[Eurosport]] |agency=Agence France-Presse |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, she became the first woman to referee in [[Ligue 1]], the top men's professional league in France.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/french-ligue-1/story/3837476/stephanie-frappart-becomes-first-woman-to-referee-ligue-1-match |title=Ligue of her own: Female ref makes historic debut |website=ESPN |date=28 April 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> The final was Frappart's fourth match as referee during the tournament, having officiated two group stage matches and a quarter-final fixture. Her compatriot Manuela Nicolosi was chosen as one of the assistant referees, along with Irish official Michelle O'Neill. [[Claudia Umpi\u00e9rrez]] of Uruguay was chosen as the fourth official, with her compatriot Luciana Mascara\u00f1a serving as the reserve assistant referee. Spaniard [[Carlos del Cerro Grande]] was named the [[video assistant referee]], presiding over the first use of the technology in the final of the Women's World Cup. His fellow countryman [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda S\u00e1nchez Mart\u00ednez]] was named as one of the assistant video assistant referees for the match, along with Mariana de Almeida of Argentina.<ref name=\"USA-NED line-ups\"/>\n\n===Team selection===\nAmerican co-captain Megan Rapinoe, who scored five goals and had three assists during the tournament, was left out of the semi-final line-up against England due to a [[pulled hamstring]]. However, she said that she expected to return ahead of the final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hays |first=Graham |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3891501/rapinoe-hammy-expects-to-be-fit-for-the-final |title=Rapinoe (hammy) expects to be 'fit for the final' |website=ESPN |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref> U.S. midfielder Rose Lavelle also had to be substituted out in the semi-final due to a hamstring injury,<ref>{{cite news |last=Killion |first=Ann |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/annkillion/article/One-more-game-for-U-S-women-who-will-play-for-14067772.php |title=One more game for U.S. women, who will play for World Cup title |website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref> though she also said that she was fit to play in the final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bird |first=Hayden |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/soccer/2019/07/03/alex-morgan-tea-celebration-criticism-england |title=Morning sports update: Former England players were not happy with Alex Morgan's tea celebration |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=3 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nDutch winger Lieke Martens, winner of [[The Best FIFA Women's Player]] in [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2017|2017]], was also listed as questionable due to a toe injury. She started in the semi-final against Sweden, previously a doubt for the match, though she was unable to make an impact and was substituted out at half-time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Evans |first=Simon |location=[[Lyon]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-worldcup-nld-swe-martens/dutch-star-martens-hopes-to-make-final-despite-injury-idUSKCN1TY30C |title=Dutch star Martens hopes to make final despite injury |website=[[Reuters]] |date=3 July 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> The team's goalkeeper, [[Sari van Veenendaal]], finished the semi-final with a swollen hand, but returned to the starting line-up for the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/usa-netherlands-key-strengths-and-areas-of-concern |title=USA\u2013Netherlands: Key strengths and areas of concern |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=5 July 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=horizontal |total_width=300\n| image1 = Megan Rapinoe (May 2019) (cropped).jpg\n| alt1 = U.S. player Megan Rapinoe jogging towards the camera\n| image2 = Rose Lavelle (36648133634).jpg\n| alt2 = U.S. player Rose Lavelle waving to a member of the audience\n| footer = [[Megan Rapinoe]] (left) and [[Rose Lavelle]] (right) scored second-half goals for the United States in the final.\n}}\n\nThe United States fielded their unusual 4\u20133\u20133 that was used by Jill Ellis during the tournament, including Megan Rapinoe, the U.S. captain for the match, after her injury that kept her from starting in the semi-final. Lieke Martens returned for the Netherlands side, while [[Shanice van de Sanden]] was placed on the bench.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bushnell |first=Henry |date=7 July 2019 |title=Megan Rapinoe returns to USWNT starting lineup for World Cup final |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/world-cup-final-starting-lineups-usa-netherlands-megan-rapinoe-2019-134645618.html |work=Yahoo Sports |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The match kicked off at 17:00 in {{convert|31|C|F}} heat, which was lower than the earlier forecasts for the ongoing [[June 2019 European heat wave|continental heat wave]].<ref name=\"NYT-Live\">{{cite news |last=Das |first=Andrew |date=7 July 2019 |title=U.S. Wins Record Fourth World Cup Title |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/07/sports/soccer/usa-vs-netherlands-score.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The match was attended by 57,900 spectators, including a large number of American fans and a stand of Dutch fans organised behind one of the goals.<ref name=\"NYT-Live\"/> French president [[Emmanuel Macron]], Dutch monarch [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|Willem-Alexander]], and several professional male and female footballers were also among those in attendance.<ref name=\"LAT-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=7 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup final: U.S. defeats Netherlands to win another title |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-uswnt-netherlands-world-cup-score-updates-20190707-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe United States started several attacks early in the match, but failed to score within the opening twelve minutes as they had in their previous six matches. The two sides traded fouls, including one that earned [[Sherida Spitse]] a yellow card in the tenth minute, but the U.S. remained in control of possession and had several chances towards goal.<ref name=\"NYT-Live\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Live\">{{cite news |last=Dure |first=Beau |date=7 July 2019 |title=USA beat Netherlands 2\u20130 to win Women's World Cup final \u2013 as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/jul/07/womens-world-cup-final-usa-netherlands-live |work=The Guardian |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> Dutch goalkeeper and captain [[Sari van Veenendaal]] made several saves to keep her shutout, including two shots before half-time from [[Sam Mewis]] and Alex Morgan. A foul on [[Rose Lavelle]] at the top of the penalty area was left uncalled, allowing the Dutch to spring a counterattack that ended with a foul on forward [[Lineth Beerensteyn]] by U.S. defender [[Abby Dahlkemper]], who earned a yellow card. In first half stoppage time, U.S. defender [[Kelley O'Hara]] and Dutch winger Lieke Martens collided heads during an aerial challenge, resulting in O'Hara being substituted at half-time for [[Ali Krieger]].<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/>\n\nAnother physical challenge, resulting in a bloody facial cut for U.S. defender [[Becky Sauerbrunn]], began the second half as the U.S. continued to have the majority of attacking chances. Dutch defender [[Stefanie van der Gragt]] kicked U.S. attacker Alex Morgan in the shoulder while attempting to control the ball in the penalty area, which was left uncalled until a VAR review by referee St\u00e9phanie Frappart awarded a penalty to the United States. Van der Gragt earned a yellow card and the penalty was scored in the 61st minute by U.S. captain Megan Rapinoe, who left Van Veenendaal standing on her line;<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |last=Wrack |first=Suzanne |date=7 July 2019 |title=Megan Rapinoe on the spot as USA beat Netherlands to win Women's World Cup |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jul/07/womens-world-cup-final-report-usa-netherlands |work=The Guardian |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> the penalty was Rapinoe's sixth goal of the tournament, winning her the Golden Boot and making her the oldest player to score in a Women's World Cup final.<ref name=\"WaPo\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |last2=Giambalvo |first2=Emily |date=7 July 2019 |title=U.S. wins Women's World Cup title with 2\u20130 defeat of Netherlands |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/07/07/uswnt-netherlands-world-cup-final/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gonzalez |first=Roger |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/womens-world-cup-final-uswnts-megan-rapinoe-opens-the-scoring-makes-history-with-penalty-kick-goal/ |title=Women's World Cup final: USWNT's Megan Rapinoe opens the scoring, makes history with penalty kick goal |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> Eight minutes later, Rose Lavelle scored the second goal of the final for the U.S. on a solo run through the Dutch defence that ended with a left-footed strike from {{convert|17|yd|m}}.<ref name=\"WaPo\"/>\n\nDown 2\u20130 and still conceding attacking chances to the U.S., the Netherlands substituted defender [[Anouk Dekker]] for forward [[Shanice van de Sanden]] and forced a save out of U.S. goalkeeper [[Alyssa Naeher]]. Van Veenendaal made several saves to deny a third goal for the United States after shots on target by Morgan, [[Tobin Heath]], and [[Crystal Dunn]].<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/> Rapinoe was substituted by Christen Press in the 79th minute, while Carli Lloyd was brought on in the last minutes of regulation time. After the end of the match, the U.S. bench spilled onto the field to celebrate the team's fourth Women's World Cup title.<ref name=\"NYT-Live\"/><ref name=\"WaPo\"/>\n\n===Details===\n<section begin=Final />{{Football box\n|date={{Start date|2019|7|7|df=y}}\n|time=17:00 <noinclude>[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]</noinclude>\n|team1={{fbw-rt|USA}}\n|score={{score link|2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Final|2\u20130|2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final}}\n|report=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches<!--/round=278517-->/match/300438259/\n|team2={{fbw|NED}}\n|goals1=\n*[[Megan Rapinoe|Rapinoe]] {{goal|61|pen.}}\n*[[Rose Lavelle|Lavelle]] {{goal|69}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]], [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]]\n|attendance=57,900<ref name=\"USA-NED match report\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/eng-52-0707-usa-ned-fulltime-pdf-3044630.pdf?cloudid=owdlkbnw1p9sf7wnlhfs |title=Match report \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n|referee=[[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]] ([[French Football Federation|France]])\n}}<section end=Final />\n<section begin=Line-ups />\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _usa19hw\n |pattern_b  = _usa19hw\n |pattern_ra = _usa19hw\n |pattern_sh = _usa19hw\n |pattern_so = _usa19wh\n |leftarm    = FFFFFF\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = FFFFFF\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = FFFFFF\n |title      = {{nowrap|United States}}<ref name=\"USA-NED line-ups\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/eng-52-0707-usa-ned-tacticalstartlist-pdf-3044546.pdf?cloudid=bnrme8aiv1jnynuvjkyx |title=Tactical Line-up \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _ned19hw\n |pattern_b  = _ned19hw\n |pattern_ra = _ned19hw\n |pattern_sh = _ned18h2\n |pattern_so = _ned19hwlong\n |leftarm    = FF6100\n |body       = FF6100\n |rightarm   = FF6100\n |shorts     = FF6100\n |socks      = FF6100\n |title      = Netherlands<ref name=\"USA-NED line-ups\"/>\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Alyssa Naeher]]\n|-\n|RB ||'''5''' ||[[Kelley O'Hara]] || || {{suboff|46}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''7''' ||[[Abby Dahlkemper]] || {{yel|42}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''4''' ||[[Becky Sauerbrunn]]\n|-\n|LB ||'''19'''||[[Crystal Dunn]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''3''' ||[[Sam Mewis]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||[[Julie Ertz]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''16'''||[[Rose Lavelle]]\n|-\n|RF ||'''17'''||[[Tobin Heath]] || || {{suboff|87}}\n|-\n|CF ||'''13'''||[[Alex Morgan]]\n|-\n|LF ||'''15'''||[[Megan Rapinoe]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || || {{suboff|79}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|DF ||'''11'''||[[Ali Krieger]] || || {{subon|46}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''23'''||[[Christen Press]] || || {{subon|79}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''10'''||[[Carli Lloyd]] || || {{subon|87}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Jill Ellis]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|[[File:USA-NED (women) 2019-07-07.svg|300px]]\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Sari van Veenendaal]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|RB ||'''2''' ||[[Desiree van Lunteren]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''6''' ||[[Anouk Dekker]] || || {{suboff|73}}\n|-\n|CB ||'''3''' ||[[Stefanie van der Gragt]] || {{yel|60}}\n|-\n|LB ||'''20'''||[[Dominique Bloodworth]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''14'''||[[Jackie Groenen]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''10'''||[[Dani\u00eblle van de Donk]]\n|-\n|CM ||'''8''' ||[[Sherida Spitse]] || {{yel|10}}\n|-\n|RF ||'''21'''||[[Lineth Beerensteyn]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''9''' ||[[Vivianne Miedema]]\n|-\n|LF ||'''11'''||[[Lieke Martens]] || || {{suboff|70}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|MF ||'''19'''||[[Jill Roord]] || || {{subon|70}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''7''' ||[[Shanice van de Sanden]] || || {{subon|73}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|[[Sarina Wiegman]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''Player of the Match:'''\n<br />[[Megan Rapinoe]] (United States)<ref name=\"POTM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/match/300438259/#potm |title=USA v Netherlands \u2013 Player of the Match |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referees]]:'''<ref name=\"USA-NED line-ups\"/>\n<br />Manuela Nicolosi ([[French Football Federation|France]])\n<br />Michelle O'Neill ([[Football Association of Ireland|Republic of Ireland]])\n<br />'''[[Assistant referee (association football)#Fourth official|Fourth official]]:'''\n<br />[[Claudia Umpi\u00e9rrez]] ([[Uruguayan Football Association|Uruguay]])\n<br />'''[[Assistant referee (association football)#Reserve assistant referee|Reserve assistant referee]]:'''\n<br />Luciana Mascara\u00f1a ([[Uruguayan Football Association|Uruguay]])\n<br />'''[[Video assistant referee]]:'''\n<br />[[Carlos del Cerro Grande]] ([[Royal Spanish Football Federation|Spain]])\n<br />'''[[Video assistant referee#Assistant video assistant referee|Assistant video assistant referees]]:'''\n<br />[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda S\u00e1nchez Mart\u00ednez]] ([[Royal Spanish Football Federation|Spain]])\n<br />Mariana de Almeida ([[Argentine Football Association|Argentina]])\n<includeonly>|}</includeonly><section end=Line-ups />\n|style=\"width:60%;vertical-align:top\"|\n'''Match rules'''<ref name=\"regulations\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/fifa-women-s-world-cup-france-2019tm-regulations.pdf?cloudid=ztloydigvm0hzcoqbtez |title=Regulations \u2013 FIFA Women's World Cup France 2019 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref>\n*90 minutes.\n*30 minutes of [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] if necessary.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still level.\n*Maximum of twelve named substitutes.\n*Maximum of three substitutions, with a fourth allowed in extra time.\n|}\n\n===Statistics===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ First half<ref>{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/eng-52-0707-usa-ned-halftime-pdf-3044587.pdf?cloudid=re1nrndj7kztsb876k92 |title=Match report: Half-time \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:100px\"|Statistic\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px\"|United States\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px\"|Netherlands\n|-\n!scope=row|Goals scored\n|0\n|0\n|-\n!scope=row|Total shots\n|5\n|2\n|-\n!scope=row|Shots on target\n|4\n|0\n|-\n!scope=row|Saves\n|0\n|4\n|-\n!scope=row|Ball possession\n|53%\n|47%\n|-\n!scope=row|Corner kicks\n|5\n|2\n|-\n!scope=row|Fouls committed\n|4\n|3\n|-\n!scope=row|Offsides\n|1\n|1\n|-\n!scope=row|Yellow cards\n|1\n|1\n|-\n!scope=row|Red cards\n|0\n|0\n|}\n{{col-3}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Second half<ref name=\"USA-NED match report\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:100px\"|Statistic\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px\"|United States\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px\"|Netherlands\n|-\n!scope=row|Goals scored\n|2\n|0\n|-\n!scope=row|Total shots\n|12\n|4\n|-\n!scope=row|Shots on target\n|5\n|1\n|-\n!scope=row|Saves\n|1\n|3\n|-\n!scope=row|Ball possession\n|53%\n|47%\n|-\n!scope=row|Corner kicks\n|3\n|0\n|-\n!scope=row|Fouls committed\n|5\n|4\n|-\n!scope=row|Offsides\n|2\n|0\n|-\n!scope=row|Yellow cards\n|0\n|1\n|-\n!scope=row|Red cards\n|0\n|0\n|}\n{{col-3}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Overall<ref name=\"USA-NED match report\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:100px\"|Statistic\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px\"|United States\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:70px\"|Netherlands\n|-\n!scope=row|Goals scored\n|2\n|0\n|-\n!scope=row|Total shots\n|17\n|6\n|-\n!scope=row|Shots on target\n|9\n|1\n|-\n!scope=row|Saves\n|1\n|7\n|-\n!scope=row|Ball possession\n|53%\n|47%\n|-\n!scope=row|Corner kicks\n|8\n|2\n|-\n!scope=row|Fouls committed\n|9\n|7\n|-\n!scope=row|Offsides\n|3\n|1\n|-\n!scope=row|Yellow cards\n|1\n|2\n|-\n!scope=row|Red cards\n|0\n|0\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Post-match==\n[[File:20141015 - PSG-Twente 084 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|Dutch goalkeeper [[Sari van Veenendaal]] won the Golden Glove award as best goalkeeper of the tournament.]]\n\nThe United States won a record-extending fourth title, and became the second team to win consecutive editions of the Women's World Cup, following Germany in 2003 and 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=Price |first=Satchel |date=7 July 2019 |title=U.S. beats Netherlands to win 2019 Women's World Cup |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/7/7/20685106/usa-netherlands-final-score-2019-world-cup-soccer |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The victory was also the first World Cup title on European soil for the U.S.<ref>{{cite news |last=McKay |first=Ben |url=https://au.sports.yahoo.com/usa-confirm-dominance-world-cup-win-184936641--spt.html |title=USA confirm dominance with World Cup win |website=Yahoo Sport Australia |agency=[[Australian Associated Press]] |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=9 July 2019}}</ref> During the 2019 tournament, the U.S. scored 26 goals to set a new record for most goals in a single Women's World Cup, surpassing the record of 25 shared by the U.S. in 1991 and Germany in 2003.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Greenspan |first=Rachel E. |date=7 July 2019 |title=All the Records the 2019 U.S. Women's Soccer Team Broke in This Year's World Cup |url=https://time.com/5621639/team-usa-2019-world-cup-records/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"statistical kit\"/> The team's [[goal difference]] of +23 also set a new tournament record.<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/the-19ers-in-numbers |title=The '19ers in numbers |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=9 July 2019 |access-date=9 July 2019}}</ref> Their World Cup unbeaten streak was also extended to 17 matches, including 12 consecutive wins.<ref name=\"LAT-Summary\"/> [[Jill Ellis]] became the first manager to win two Women's World Cup titles, amid criticism from fans over her style of management.<ref>{{cite news |last=Schaerlaeckens |first=Leander |date=7 July 2019 |title=Jill Ellis was vindicated at this Women's World Cup |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/jill-ellis-was-vindicated-at-this-womens-world-cup-195146344.html |work=Yahoo Sports |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Aimee |location=Lyon |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/05/football/jill-ellis-uswnt-womens-world-cup-spt-intl/index.html |title=Jill Ellis: The shy girl from England who became US Soccer's record-breaking head coach |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=6 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> On 10 July, the team were honoured with a [[ticker tape parade]] down the Canyon of Heroes in [[New York City]] and received their third [[Outstanding Team ESPY Award]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Burke |first=Minyvonne |date=10 July 2019 |title=U.S. Women's World Cup champions cheered by tens of thousands at NYC ticker-tape parade |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/sports/u-s-women-s-world-cup-champions-celebrated-thousands-nyc-n1028156 |publisher=NBC News |access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=10 July 2019 |title=USWNT named best team; Messi, Ibra win ESPYs |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3898240/uswnt-named-best-team-messiibra-win-espys |publisher=ESPN |access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nMegan Rapinoe was named the player of the match,<ref name=\"POTM\"/> and was awarded the [[FIFA Women's World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Golden Ball]] as the best player of the tournament. She also won the [[FIFA Women's World Cup awards#Golden Boot|Golden Boot]] as the top scorer of the tournament with six goals and three assists, while Alex Morgan won the Silver Boot with the same tallies; Rapinoe won the award on the second tie-breaker, having played fewer minutes.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup: USA's Megan Rapinoe wins Golden Boot |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48902004 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> At the age of 34, Rapinoe became the oldest player to win the Golden Ball and Golden Boot awards.<ref>{{cite news |last=Howard |first=Chelsea |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/fifa-womens-world-cup/womens-world-cup-2019-10-crazy-facts-from-uswnts-big-final-win-over-netherlands/ar-AADZa9z |title=Women's World Cup 2019: 10 crazy facts from USWNT's big final win over Netherlands |website=[[MSN]] |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> Rose Lavelle won the Bronze Ball award, while Dutch goalkeeper Sari van Veenendaal won the [[FIFA Women's World Cup awards#Golden Glove and Best Goalkeeper|Golden Glove]] award as the best goalkeeper of the tournament; her eight saves in the final were the most during any knockout stage match in the 2019 tournament.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 July 2019 |title=Sensational Rapinoe showered with gold |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/sensational-rapinoe-showered-with-gold-3044723 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Garry |first=Tom |date=7 July 2019 |title=USA beat Netherlands to win fourth title |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48897032 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nRapinoe became the second player to start in three Women's World Cup finals, after [[Birgit Prinz]] of Germany (1995, 2003 and 2007). Additionally, Tobin Heath, Ali Krieger, Carli Lloyd and Alex Morgan joined them as the only players to make an appearance in three finals.<ref name=\"numbers\"/> Rapinoe's goal made her the first player to convert a penalty outside of a shoot-out in a Women's World Cup final, as German goalkeeper [[Nadine Angerer]] saved the only previous final penalty taken by [[Marta (footballer)|Marta]] of Brazil in 2007. The goal also meant that Rapinoe became the oldest player to score in a final, surpassing teammate Carli Lloyd who scored a hat-trick in the 2015 final at the age of 32 years and 354 days.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.safa.net/2019/07/07/usa-defeat-netherlands-lift-fifa-wwc-record-4-times/ |title=USA defeat Netherlands to lift FIFA WWC a record 4 times |website=[[South African Football Association]] |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe United States will receive $4 million (3.5 million euros) in prize money as the winners of the tournament, while the Netherlands will receive $2.6 million (2.3 million euros) as runners-up.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hes |first=Abigail |date=8 June 2019 |title=The 2019 Women's World Cup prize money is $30 million\u20147.5% of the Men's World Cup prize |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/06/07/the-2019-womens-world-cup-prize-money-is-30-million.html |publisher=[[CNBC]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=7 July 2019 |title=Wat cashen de Oranje Leeuwinnen ondanks verlies in WK-finale? |language=Dutch |trans-title=What does the Oranje Leeuwinnen earn despite losing in the World Cup final? |url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/1355570539/wat-cashen-de-oranje-leeuwinnen-ondanks-verlies-in-wk-finale |work=[[De Telegraaf]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The U.S. team will also play a four-match victory tour that will entitle them to a share of profits, totalling approximately $250,000 per player.<ref>{{cite news |last=Das |first=Andrew |date=7 July 2019 |title=What's a World Cup Title Worth? For U.S. Women, Six Figures and Counting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/07/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-bonuses.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The monetary prizes, along with small bonuses from the [[United States Soccer Federation]], were criticised as being unfair and [[gender pay gap|discriminatory]] compared to those offered to men's teams; fans in the stadium chanted \"Equal pay!\" during FIFA president [[Gianni Infantino]]'s appearance at the trophy ceremony alongside French president Emmanuel Macron.<ref>{{cite news |last=Silverstein |first=Jason |date=7 July 2019 |title=U.S. Women's World Cup victory sets off immediate calls for equal pay |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/us-womens-world-cup-win-sets-off-immediate-calls-for-equal-pay-today-2019-07-07/ |publisher=[[CBS News]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Evans |first=Simon |date=7 July 2019 |title=Landmark women's World Cup set to be game-changer |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-worldcup-usa-nld-landmark-idUSKCN1U20RT |publisher=[[Reuters]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> Several media personalities and sportspeople from the U.S. also mentioned the issue while congratulating the team on their victory.<ref>{{cite news |last=DeSantis |first=Rachel |date=7 July 2019 |title=Celebrities React to USWNT's World Cup Victory \u2014 and Call for Equal Pay |url=https://people.com/sports/uswnt-world-cup-victory-celebrities-react/ |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> In response, Senator [[Joe Manchin]] introduced a bill in the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] that would make equal pay for the women's team a requirement for federal funding for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 men's World Cup]], which is planned to be partially hosted by the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kelly |first=Caroline |date=9 July 2019 |title=Senate Democrat wants to halt federal 2026 World Cup funding until USWNT receives equal pay |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/09/politics/joe-manchin-womens-soccer-equal-pay-bill-trnd/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=9 July 2019}}</ref> U.S. President [[Donald Trump]], who had criticised Rapinoe's anthem protest and comments about rejecting a [[White House]] visit, also congratulated the team alongside former presidents [[Barack Obama]] and [[Bill Clinton]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Allen |first=Scott |date=7 July 2019 |title=Trumps, Obamas, Clintons congratulate USWNT after World Cup triumph |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/07/07/melania-trump-michelle-obama-congratulate-uswnt-world-cup-triumph/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2019, the United States Soccer Federation announced that head coach Jill Ellis would step down upon completion of the team's U.S. victory tour in October 2019. Following her departure, she will continue to work as an ambassador for U.S. Soccer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2019/07/jill-ellis-to-step-down-as-uswnt-head-coach |title=Jill Ellis to Step Down as U.S. Women's National Team Head Coach |website=United States Soccer Federation |date=30 July 2019 |access-date=30 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/ellis-to-relinquish-us-reins |title=Ellis to relinquish USA reins |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=30 July 2019 |access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. team was named the Athlete of the Year by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite news |last=Gregory |first=Sean |date=10 December 2019 |title=Time Athlete of the Year: U.S. Women's Soccer Team |url=https://time.com/athlete-of-the-year-2019-us-womens-soccer-team/ |work=Time |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref> while Rapinoe was awarded the [[Ballon d'Or F\u00e9minin]] and named the [[Sports Illustrated Sportsperson of the Year|''Sports Illustrated'' Sportsperson of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Boren |first=Cindy |date=9 December 2019 |title=Megan Rapinoe is Sports Illustrated's Sportsperson of the Year, only the fourth woman chosen alone |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/12/09/megan-rapinoe-is-sports-illustrateds-sportsperson-year-only-fourth-woman-chosen-alone/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Broadcasting===\n\nThe international broadcast of the match garnered an average of 82.18&nbsp;million live viewers and 260&nbsp;million total viewers, setting a new tournament record.<ref>{{cite press release |date=18 October 2019 |title=FIFA Women's World Cup 2019 watched by more than 1 billion |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/fifa-women-s-world-cup-2019tm-watched-by-more-than-1-billion |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> The U.S. broadcast of the match on terrestrial television station [[Fox (network)|Fox]] drew an average of 14.3&nbsp;million, outranking the [[2018 FIFA World Cup Final|2018 men's final]] (which did not feature the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S.]]) but falling short of the 2015 Women's World Cup broadcast that was broadcast during U.S. [[prime time]] rather than late morning.<ref>{{cite news |last=Strauss |first=Ben |date=8 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup final delivers viewers for Fox, despite early start time |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/07/08/womens-world-cup-final-delivers-viewers-fox-despite-early-start-time/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> An additional 1.6&nbsp;million Americans watched the match on [[Telemundo]] in Spanish, and streaming audiences for Fox averaged 289,000 viewers.<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{cite news |last=Porter |first=Rick |date=8 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup Final Draws Bigger Audience Than 2018 Men's Final |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/womens-world-cup-final-outdraws-2018-mens-final-us-ratings-1222814 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the Netherlands, the final was watched by 5.5&nbsp;million people, an estimated 88&nbsp;percent of people with television access.<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/> The Brazilian broadcast on [[TV Globo]] and its partners was watched by 19.9&nbsp;million people (a 41.7 percent share), setting a new women's football record. Large audiences were also reported in France (5.9&nbsp;million), Germany (5.1&nbsp;million), Sweden (1.5&nbsp;million) and the United Kingdom (3.2&nbsp;million).<ref name=\"Hollywood\"/><ref>{{cite news |date=9 July 2019 |title=France 2019 Final sets viewing records in participating and neutral territories |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/france-2019-final-sets-viewing-records-in-participating-and-neutral-territories |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|FIFA Women's World Cup 2019 Final}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/index.html}}\n\n{{2019 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{United States women's national soccer team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fifa Women's World Cup Final 2019}}\n[[Category:2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:FIFA Women's World Cup Finals|2019]]\n[[Category:2018\u201319 in French women's football]]\n[[Category:United States women's national soccer team matches]]\n[[Category:United States at the 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:Netherlands women's national football team matches]]\n[[Category:Netherlands at the 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:Netherlands\u2013United States relations|FIFA Women's World Cup Final]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Lyon]]\n[[Category:21st century in Lyon]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title            = 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final\n| image            = FIFA Women's World Cup 2019 Final - US team on podium (4).jpg\n| image_size       = 250\n| caption          = The U.S. team lifts the championship trophy\n| event            = [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]]\n| team1            = [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]]\n| team1association = {{flagdeco|USA|size=30px}}\n| team1score       = 2\n| team2            = [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]]\n| team2association = {{flagdeco|NED|size=30px}}\n| team2score       = 0\n| details          =\n| date             = {{Start date|2019|7|7|df=y}}\n| stadium          = [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]]\n| city             = [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]]\n| woman_player1    = [[Megan Rapinoe]] {{nowrap|(United States)}}<ref name=\"POTM\"/>\n| referee          = [[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]] ([[French Football Federation|France]])<ref name=\"referee\"/>\n| attendance       = 57,900<ref name=\"match report\"/>\n| weather          = Partly cloudy<br />{{convert|30|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|abbr=on}}<br />41% [[humidity]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/eng-52-0707-usa-ned-start-pdf-3044519.pdf?cloudid=rktlyniz7plxsaolhrim |title=Start list \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches/match/300438259/#match-info |title=Match Facts \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n| previous         = [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2015]]\n| next             = ''2023''\n}}\nThe '''2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final''' was a [[Women's association football|football]] match which determined the winner of the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]]. It was the eighth final of the [[FIFA Women's World Cup]], a quadrennial tournament contested by the [[List of women's national association football teams|women's national teams]] of the member associations of [[FIFA]]. The match was played on 7 July 2019 at the [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]], a suburb of [[Lyon]], France.\n\nThe final was contested by the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]], the defending champion, and the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]], in their first final. The United States won 2\u20130, earning their second consecutive and fourth overall Women's World Cup title, with second-half goals scored by co-captain [[Megan Rapinoe]] from the penalty spot and [[Rose Lavelle]]. With their victory, the U.S. joined [[Germany women's national football team|Germany]] as the second team to win consecutive titles. The team's coach, [[Jill Ellis]], became the first manager to win two Women's World Cup titles.\n\nEach finalist was the reigning champion of their own respective confederation, with the United States having won the [[2018 CONCACAF Women's Championship]] and the Netherlands having won [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017]].\n\n==Venue==\n{{Further|Parc Olympique Lyonnais}}\n[[File:Parc OL.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]] hosted the final.]]\n\nThe final was held at the [[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]] in [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]], a suburb of [[Lyon]]. During the tournament, the stadium was referred to as the Stade de Lyon by FIFA.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://img.fifa.com/image/upload/lyydkcj1chj8wwmorgbt.pdf |title=Match Schedule FIFA Women's World Cup France 2019 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=8 December 2018 |access-date=8 December 2018}}</ref> The venue has a seating capacity of 57,900, and hosted both semi-final matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/destination/stadiums/stadium/5043845/ |title=Stade de Lyon |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=22 June 2019}}</ref> The stadium was announced as the final venue when France was confirmed as host on 19 March 2015,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/La-france-organisera-la-coupe-du-monde-2019/544452 |title=La France organisera la Coupe du monde 2019! |trans-title=France will host the 2019 World Cup! |publisher=[[L'\u00c9quipe]] |date=19 March 2015 |access-date=26 June 2019 |language=French}}</ref> with the stadium officially confirmed to host the semi-finals and final in September 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/official-slogan-and-emblem-of-fifa-women-s-world-cup-france-2019-launc-2908450 |title=Official Slogan and Emblem of FIFA Women's World Cup France 2019 launched today |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=19 September 2017 |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref> The stadium is home venue of [[Ligue 1]] club [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]], opening in January 2016 to replace their previous stadium, the [[Stade de Gerland]].<ref>{{cite news |date=11 January 2016 |title=Lyon thump Troyes 4\u20131 at new stadium |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/sport/archives/2016/01/11/2003636933 |work=[[Taipei Times]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref> It has also hosted several [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] matches for the [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|club's women's side]], which is the most successful in European history.<ref>{{cite news |date=7 June 2019 |title=The heart of women's football: Why Lyon is the perfect city to host the World Cup |url=https://www.euronews.com/2019/06/06/the-heart-of-women-s-football-why-lyon-is-the-perfect-city-to-host-the-world-cup |publisher=[[Euronews]] |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=13 April 2019 |title=Record crowd watches OL thrash PSG at Groupama Stadium |url=https://www.ol.fr/en/contents/articles/2019/04/13/record-crowd-watches-ol-thrash-psg-groupama-stadium |publisher=Olympique Lyonnais |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the project for the new stadium was agreed upon by the government and commune of D\u00e9cines.<ref>{{cite news |title=Le grand stade est relanc\u00e9 |url=http://www.football365.fr/france/infos-clubs/lyon/article_270702_lyon-ol-land-Le-grand-stade-est-relance.shtml |work=France Soir |date=16 October 2008 |access-date=30 October 2009}}</ref> Stadium construction started in mid 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stadedelyonconstruction.fr/france/stadelyon/stadelyon.nsf/fr/intranet?openagent&Niveau1=Actualites&Document=045A6B5EE8A2A4BEC1257CE40030632C |title=3e trimestre 2013: c'est parti! |trans-title=Third quarter 2013: let's go! |website=stadedelyonconstruction.fr |date=30 July 2013 |access-date=26 June 2019 |language=French |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402141609/http://www.stadedelyonconstruction.fr/france/stadelyon/stadelyon.nsf/fr/intranet?openagent&Niveau1=Actualites&Document=045A6B5EE8A2A4BEC1257CE40030632C |archive-date=2 April 2015}}</ref> and finished in late 2015 at a cost of \u20ac450 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.journaldunet.com/solutions/dsi/1168948-transformation-numerique-olympique-lyonnais-stade-des-lumieres/ |title=Comment l'Olympique Lyonnais veut passer \u00e0 l'\u00e8re du stade connect\u00e9 |trans-title=How Olympique Lyonnais wants to move into the era of the connected stadium |work=Le Journal du Net |date=7 December 2015 |access-date=26 June 2019 |language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lepoint.fr/sport/football/grand-stade-de-lyon-premier-pari-gagne-pour-jean-michel-aulas-07-01-2016-2007791_1858.php |title=Grand stade de Lyon : premier pari gagn\u00e9 pour Jean-Michel Aulas |trans-title=Grand Stade de Lyon: first win for Jean-Michel Aulas |website=[[Le Point]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |date=7 January 2016 |access-date=27 June 2019 |language=French}}</ref> The stadium was chosen as a venue for [[UEFA Euro 2016]], where it hosted six matches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stade de Lyon |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/hosts/france/city=2156/stadium/index.html |access-date=15 September 2017 |publisher=UEFA}}</ref> The stadium also hosted the [[2017 Coupe de la Ligue Final]] and [[2018 UEFA Europa League Final]].<ref>{{cite news |date=9 December 2016 |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=2398004.html |title=Parc OL chosen to host 2018 UEFA Europa League Final |publisher=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Coupe de la Ligue hits the road! |url=http://www.ligue1.com/coupeLigue/article/the-coupe-de-la-ligue-hits-the-road.htm |access-date=15 September 2017 |publisher=Ligue 1 |date=2 September 2016}}</ref> Outside of football, the Parc Olympique Lyonnais has hosted several musical performances,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Frisulio |first1=Elisa |title=A Lyon, Coldplay a emball\u00e9 le Parc OL |url=http://www.20minutes.fr/lyon/2083431-20170609-lyon-coldplay-emballe-parc-ol |access-date=15 September 2017 |work=20 Minutes |date=9 June 2017 |language=French}}</ref> as well as [[ice hockey]] and [[rugby union]] matches,<ref>{{cite news |title=Winter Game : bient\u00f4t du hockey sur glace au Parc OL !|trans-title=Winter Game: ice hockey coming soon at Parc OL! |url=https://www.lyonmag.com/article/78490/winter-game-bientot-du-hockey-sur-glace-au-parc-ol |access-date=4 April 2016 |publisher=Lyon Mag |date=12 February 2016}}</ref> including the [[2016 European Rugby Champions Cup Final|Rugby Champions Cup]] and [[2015\u201316 European Rugby Challenge Cup#Final|Rugby Challenge Cup]] finals of 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.epcrugby.com/news/30996.php#.WZASrXeGPow |title=Lyon to host 2016 Champions Cup and Challenge Cup finals with Edinburgh chosen for 2017 |publisher=European Professional Club Rugby |date=17 June 2015 |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref> The stadium is planned to host matches for the [[2023 Rugby World Cup]] and the men and women's football tournaments at the [[2024 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The 9 stadiums for 2023 RWC in France |url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Rugby/SouthAfrica2023/the-9-stadiums-for-2023-rwc-in-france-20171115 |access-date=7 May 2018 |publisher=Sport 24 |date=15 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stade de Lyon |url=http://www.paris2024.org/en/article/stade-de-lyon |publisher=Paris 2024 |access-date=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Jillian Ellis 2015.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|U.S. coach [[Jill Ellis]] was vying to become the first manager to win two Women's World Cup titles.]]\n\nFor the first time since [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2007]], and fifth time overall (along with [[1991 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|1991]], [[1995 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|1995]] and [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2003]]), the final featured a European team, as the continent took seven of the eight places in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ramsay |first=George |last2=Lewis |first2=Aimee |date=25 June 2019 |title=Late Netherlands penalty breaks Japan's hearts at Women's World Cup |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/football/womens-world-cup-last-16-italy-china-netherlands-japan-spt-intl/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 June 2019}}</ref> The previous two finals were contested by [[Japan women's national football team|Japan]] and the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]].<ref name=\"winners\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/-676193.pdf?cloudid=e2vlheu4dbnfjyje0aoc |title=FIFA Competition winners at a glance |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref> The match was the first final since 1991 to feature a [[CONCACAF|North American]] side against a [[UEFA|European]] side.<ref name=\"winners\"/> The match was also the first final of a women's or men's World Cup to feature the defending champions against the reigning European champions.<ref name=\"UEFA\"/>\n\nThe match was a record-extending fifth Women's World Cup final for the United States, who were the defending champions and record winners of the competition with three titles. They won the inaugural final in 1991 against [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]], before winning their second title in [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|1999]] as hosts via a penalty shoot-out victory against [[China women's national football team|China PR]]. They made their next appearance in the [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2011 final]], losing on penalties to Japan, before securing their third title in the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2015]] rematch against Japan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/highlights-heroines-and-stats-from-the-first-seven-finals |title=Highlights and heroines from the first seven Finals |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=4 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> In the previous seven editions of the tournament, the U.S. never finished outside of the top three.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/womens-world-cup-2019-uswnt-wants-continue-dominant-history/hhs4yay1mqpl1xiv1fn3l3f3k |title=Women's World Cup 2019: USWNT wants to continue dominant history |website=[[Sporting News]] |date=10 June 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref> The fixture was the third consecutive appearance in the final for the United States, setting a competition record.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=548679 |title=U.S. outlasts England to reach World Cup final |publisher=ESPN |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Jill Ellis]] became the third manager to reach two Women's World Cup finals, after [[Even Pellerud]] for Norway (in 1991 and 1995) and [[Norio Sasaki]] for Japan (in 2011 and 2015), both with one win and one loss in the final.<ref name=\"statistical kit\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/statistical-kit-milestones-and-superlatives-x6371.pdf?cloudid=i9hyrqdeoftzwuhhqw4p |title=Statistical kit, FIFA Women's World Cup France 2019: Milestones & Superlatives \u2013 Draw edition |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=11 April 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> With her counterpart [[Sarina Wiegman]], the match was the second final in which both teams have a female coach, after the 2003 matchup between [[Tina Theune]] of Germany and [[Marika Domanski-Lyfors]] of Sweden.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/ellis-wiegman-head-to-head-3044253 |title=Ellis and Wiegman: A closer look at the Final's coaches |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=6 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe match was the first Women's World Cup final for the Netherlands in their second tournament appearance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/history-beckons-in-la-grande-finale |title=History beckons in La Grande Finale |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=6 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> They were the fourth European country (after Germany, Norway and [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]]) and eighth overall to reach a Women's World Cup final, and the first new finalist since Japan in 2011.<ref name=\"winners\"/> In the Netherlands only prior tournament appearance, in [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015]], they were eliminated in the round of 16 by defending champions and eventual runners-up Japan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/fifa-women-s-world-cup-japan-scores-early-late-to-sink-dutch-1.3125237 |title=FIFA Women's World Cup: Japan scores early, late to sink Dutch |website=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=24 June 2015 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe match is the eighth meeting between the United States and the Netherlands, and the first competitive fixture as all prior matches were [[Exhibition game|friendlies]]. The sides first met in 1991, which the Netherlands won 4\u20133, but the U.S. have won all six subsequent meetings, most recently a 3\u20131 win in September 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2019/07/uswnt-vs-netherlands-match-history-preview-five-things-to-know |title=Five Things To Know About: Netherlands |website=[[United States Soccer Federation]] |date=6 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Route to the final==\n{{Further|2019 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#99CCFF;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | United States\n! Round\n! colspan=\"2\" | Netherlands\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#C1E0FF;\"\n| Opponents\n| Result\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group stage|Group stage]]\n| Opponents\n| Result\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|THA}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F#United States vs Thailand|13\u20130]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Match 1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|NZL}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E#New Zealand vs Netherlands|1\u20130]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|CHI}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F#United States vs Chile|3\u20130]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Match 2\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|CMR}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E#Netherlands vs Cameroon|3\u20131]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|SWE}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F#Sweden vs United States|2\u20130]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Match 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|CAN}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E#Netherlands vs Canada|2\u20131]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''[[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F|Group F]] winners'''\n<center>{{2019 FIFA Women's World Cup group tables|Group F|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=USA}}</center>\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Final standings\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''[[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E|Group E]] winners'''\n<center>{{2019 FIFA Women's World Cup group tables|Group E|only_pld_pts=yes|showteam=NED}}</center>\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#C1E0FF;\"\n| Opponents\n| Result\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage|Knockout stage]]\n| Opponents\n| Result\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|ESP}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Spain vs United States|2\u20131]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Round of 16\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|JPN}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Netherlands vs Japan|2\u20131]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|FRA}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#France vs United States|2\u20131]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Quarter-finals\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|ITA}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Italy vs Netherlands|2\u20130]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|ENG}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#England vs United States|2\u20131]]\n| style=\"background:#C1E0FF;\" | Semi-finals\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{fbw|SWE}}\n| [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Netherlands vs Sweden|1\u20130]] {{aet}}\n|}\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Alex Morgan May19.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|[[Alex Morgan]] scored six times for the United States, including five in their opening match|alt=Footballer Alex Morgan, pictured jogging in a red U.S. uniform with the number 13.]]\n\nThe United States is the most successful team in women's football, having won three Women's World Cups in four previous final appearances and four [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic]] gold medals.<ref>{{cite news |date=18 August 2017 |title=32 years of USWNT glory |url=https://www.fifa.com/womens-football/news/32-years-of-uswnt-glory-2904417 |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kann |first=Drew |date=5 July 2019 |title=Yes, the US women's soccer team is dominant. That's because most of the world is playing catch-up |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/16/us/uswnt-dominance-womens-soccer-world-cup-history-explained/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The team had never finished below third place in all eight editions of the World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Michael |date=4 July 2016 |title=On the Fourth of July, the 10 most memorable goals in US soccer history |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jul/04/usa-soccer-special-goals-fourth-of-july |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> [[Jill Ellis]] was appointed as interim head coach of the team in 2014, following the firing of [[Tom Sermanni]] between major tournaments, and oversaw qualification for the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 World Cup]] using a core inherited from earlier cycles.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hays |first=Graham |date=10 June 2015 |title=Why Jill Ellis Is The Right Coach To Help U.S. Women Reclaim World Cup |url=http://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/2015worldcup/article/13049184/how-jill-ellis-became-highest-profile-women-coach-world |publisher=ESPN W |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The United States had reached their second consecutive [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|final]] in 2015, playing in a rematch of the [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup Final|2011 final]] in which they had lost to Japan. The Americans won 5\u20132, including a first-half hat-trick by [[Carli Lloyd]], to secure their third Women's World Cup title\u2014their first since [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup|1999]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Longman |first=Jer\u00e9 |date=5 July 2015 |title=In a Rout and a Romp, U.S. Takes World Cup |page=A1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/06/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-usa-defeats-japan-to-win-title.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> Following an early quarter-final exit at the [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Olympics]], Ellis adjusted the team's usual formation and adopted a 4\u20133\u20133 with an emphasis on faster play under the direction of new call-ups.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=23 June 2019 |title=Jill Ellis quietly sits at the heart of U.S. juggernaut in Women's World Cup |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/23/jill-ellis-quietly-sits-heart-us-juggernaut-womens-world-cup/ |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=5 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup: Americans made sweeping changes to begin journey to finals |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-usa-womens-world-cup-journey-20190705-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The United States qualified for the 2019 Women's World Cup by winning the [[2018 CONCACAF Women's Championship]], outscoring their opponents 26\u20130 and defeating [[Canada women's national soccer team|Canada]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news |date=17 October 2018 |title=USA Claims 2018 CONCACAF Women's Championship Title with 2\u20130 Defeat of Regional Rival Canada |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2018/10/usa-claims-2018-concacaf-womens-championship-title-with-20-defeat-of-regional-rival-canada |publisher=U.S. Soccer |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. team, entering the tournament ranked first in the [[FIFA Women's World Rankings|FIFA World Rankings]],<ref name=\"ranking\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/ranking-table/women/rank/ranking_20190329/ |title=The FIFA Women's World Ranking: 29 March 2019 |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=29 March 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707080319/https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/ranking-table/women/rank/ranking_20190329/ |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> were drawn into [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group F|Group F]] and opened their title defence with a 13\u20130 victory against [[Thailand women's national football team|Thailand]], setting a new tournament record for largest margin of victory and goals in a match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Murray |first=Caitlin |date=11 June 2019 |title=Ruthless USA break World Cup record as they hit 13 past hapless Thailand |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/11/usa-thailand-uswnt-womens-world-cup-soccer-match-report |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> [[Alex Morgan]] scored five goals, equalling a one-match record set by compatriot [[Michelle Akers]] in 1991, and several of her teammates earned their first World Cup goals in their debuts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Anne M. |date=11 June 2019 |title=Alex Morgan has 5 goals as US routs Thailand 13\u20130 |url=https://www.apnews.com/4fedff426fff470c8d78c79ee1727373 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> The U.S. team were later criticised for [[goal celebration|celebrating]] their later goals during the match, with some media commentators and former players calling it disrespectful,<ref>{{cite news |last=Oliveira |first=Nelson |date=12 June 2019 |title=U.S. women's national team faces backlash for celebrating massive win against Thailand |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/ny-women-national-team-criticized-for-celebrating-20190612-dv4zgqmkoff2hhywuls22jrufa-story.html |work=[[New York Daily News]] |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> but the celebrations were defended by other media commentators, the team's players and members of the opposing Thai bench.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wahl |first=Grant |date=11 June 2019 |title=USWNT's Historic Rout of Thailand and the Question of Sportsmanship |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/06/11/usa-thailand-rout-celebrations-goals-jill-ellis-alex-morgan |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Guy |last2=Scott |first2=Andy |date=12 June 2019 |title=USWNT face backlash over goal celebrations in record World Cup victory |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/90minutes/ct-90mins-uswnt-face-backlash-over-goal-celebrations-in-record-world-cup-victory-20190612-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |agency=AFP |access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref> Ellis then fielded a squad of reserve players in a 3\u20130 win over debutants [[Chile women's national football team|Chile]], which included Carli Lloyd's pair of goals and a missed penalty kick.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keh |first=Andrew |date=16 June 2019 |title=New Faces, Same Result: U.S. Rolls Again at World Cup |page=D1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/16/sports/usa-chile-womens-world-cup.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The U.S. closed out its group by winning 2\u20130 against [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]], advancing with three [[shutout]] victories and outscoring opponents 18\u20130, a group stage record in the Women's World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keh |first=Andrew |date=20 June 2019 |title=U.S. Storms Past Sweden, Posting Third Straight World Cup Shutout |page=B9 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/20/sports/uswnt-sweden-score.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the round of 16, the U.S. played [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group B|Group B]] runners-up [[Spain women's national football team|Spain]], who conceded an early penalty in the seventh minute that was converted by captain [[Megan Rapinoe]]. Spanish forward [[Jennifer Hermoso]] found an equaliser within three minutes after capitalising on a defensive error near the top of the box, shooting from distance to beat goalkeeper [[Alyssa Naeher]] and end her shutout streak. The U.S. were awarded a second penalty kick after a foul in the box on [[Rose Lavelle]] and won the match 2\u20131 on another conversion by Rapinoe in the 75th minute per instruction from Ellis, after Morgan initially looked set to take the kick.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Steven |last2=Bogage |first2=Jacob |date=24 June 2019 |title='Winning by any means possible'; U.S. grinds past Spain to World Cup quarterfinals |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/24/uswnt-spain-world-cup/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gonzalez |first=Roger |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/uswnts-alex-morgan-explains-why-megan-rapinoe-was-the-penalty-kick-taker-and-addresses-injury-concerns/ |title=USWNT's Alex Morgan explains why Megan Rapinoe was the penalty-kick taker and addresses injury concerns |website=CBS Sports |date=24 June 2019 |access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> The Americans were then matched against hosts [[France women's national football team|France]], winners of Group A and a tournament favourite, in the quarter-finals. This was the first time the U.S. had faced the tournament hosts of the Women's World Cup.<ref name=\"UEFA\"/> Rapinoe opened the scoring in the fifth minute, with a free kick that was driven low and through several players, and added a second in the 65th minute by finishing a cut-back cross from [[Tobin Heath]] in the box. French defender [[Wendie Renard]] scored a consolation goal in the 81st minute on a headed corner kick, but the U.S. held on to win 2\u20131 and eliminate the hosts.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=28 June 2019 |title=Women' World Cup recap: U.S. beats France 2\u20131 on two Megan Rapinoe goals |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-us-france-uswnt-world-cup-live-soccer-20190628-story.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. played [[England women's national football team|England]] in the semi-finals, but were without Rapinoe due to a hamstring injury that kept her out of the starting line-up. Her replacement, [[Christen Press]], scored the opening goal in the tenth minute on a header in the box; English forward [[Ellen White (footballer)|Ellen White]] then volleyed a shot from inside the box in the 19th minute to earn her team an equaliser. Alex Morgan restored the U.S. lead in the 31st minute, the first player in Women's World Cup history to score on her birthday,<ref>{{cite news |last=Roscher |first=Liz |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/alex-morgan-makes-history-and-gives-uswnt-the-lead-with-teasipping-birthday-goal-194734846.html |title=Alex Morgan makes history and gives USWNT the lead with tea-sipping birthday goal |website=[[Yahoo Sports]] |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> finishing a cross by [[Lindsey Horan]] with a header that she celebrated with a controversial tea-sipping gesture.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lou |first=Michelle |date=5 July 2019 |title=Alex Morgan says criticism of her tea-sipping celebration illustrates a double standard |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/07/05/sport/alex-morgan-defends-sipping-tea-trnd/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> White scored an apparent second equaliser in the 67th minute, but was ruled offside by a [[video assistant referee]] (VAR) decision. A VAR decision in the 82nd minute determined that White was fouled in the penalty area by defender [[Becky Sauerbrunn]] and awarded a penalty to England. The resulting penalty was struck by captain [[Steph Houghton]] and saved by Alyssa Naeher, the first penalty save by a U.S. goalkeeper in the Women's World Cup outside of a shoot-out,<ref>{{cite news |last=Howard |first=Chelsea |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/soccer/news/womens-world-cup-2019-uswnt-gives-alyssa-naeher-praise-game-changing-penalty-save/z30fzwccyprn1rk1azdi3qmb0 |title=Women's World Cup 2019: USWNT gives Alyssa Naeher praise for game-changing penalty save |website=[[Sporting News]] |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> ensuring a 2\u20131 victory for the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Louise |date=2 July 2019 |title=Alex Morgan heads USA past England into Women's World Cup final |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jul/02/usa-england-womens-world-cup-match-report |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Steven |last2=Bogage |first2=Jacob |date=2 July 2019 |title=The U.S. is in the World Cup final with a stop of penalty and a spot of tea |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/07/02/uswnt-england-world-cup/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The U.S. reached their third consecutive Women's World Cup final by winning all six matches without trailing. Their semi-final win set a new tournament record for longest winning streak with eleven wins since 2015,<ref name=\"chicago tribune\">{{cite news |last=Peterson |first=Anne M. |date=2 July 2019 |title=U.S. beats England 2\u20131 to reach 3rd straight Women's World Cup final |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/soccer/ct-world-cup-united-states-england-megan-rapinoe-20190702-zqsi5v5smjarvnxvfakf6b4kha-zqsi5v5smjarvnxvfakf6b4kha-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> as well as a record sixteen World Cup matches undefeated.<ref>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup-humble-beginnings-global-event/ |title=FIFA Women's World Cup: From humble beginnings to global event |website=[[Sportsnet]] |date=3 June 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707093510/https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup-humble-beginnings-global-event/ |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hays |first1=Graham |last2=Hamilton |first2=Tom |location=Lyon |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3890943/pressmorgan-score-to-lead-uswnt-past-england-and-into-womens-world-cup-final |title=Press, Morgan score to lead USWNT past England and into Women's World Cup final |website=ESPN |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707093729/https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3890943/pressmorgan-score-to-lead-uswnt-past-england-and-into-womens-world-cup-final |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> They scored 24 goals en route to the final, including one in the opening twelve minutes of each match, coming close to the single-tournament record of 25.<ref name=\"LAT-Coaches\">{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=6 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup final: U.S. and Netherlands coaches making history |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-usa-netherlands-world-cup-final-20190706-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=6 July 2019 |title=Dutch need to stop US from scoring early in World Cup final |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/07/06/dutch-need-to-stop-us-from-scoring-early-in-world-cup-final/39659085/ |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\n[[File:20170716 WEURO NED NOR 3522 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.8|Dutch winger [[Lieke Martens]] scored twice in their round of 16 victory|alt=Footballer Lieke Martens prepares to kick the ball with her outstretched left foot.]]\n\nThe Netherlands, nicknamed the Oranje, first qualified for a major women's tournament in 2009, reaching the semi-finals of their first [[UEFA European Championship]], and qualified for their first FIFA Women's World Cup in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |date=12 April 2019 |title=Wiegman: We have a dream |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/wiegman-netherlands-have-womens-world-cup-dream#sarina-wiegman-delirious-with-joy-after-winning-the-uefa-women-s-euro |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The team's rapid improvement in international competition was credited to the establishment of a [[Eredivisie (women)|professional club league]] in 2007 with investment from the [[Royal Dutch Football Association]]; the league later merged to form a [[BeNe League|combined Belgian\u2013Dutch competition]] in 2012 and split again in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=4 July 2019 |title=Netherlands looks to add Women's World Cup title to European championship |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-usa-netherlands-world-cup-final-20190704-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Eredivisie |url=https://www.knvb.com/competitions/womens-eredivisie |publisher=[[Royal Dutch Football Association]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> In the 2015 Women's World Cup, the Dutch side finished third in their group with a 1\u20131\u20131 record and advanced to the round of 16, where they lost 2\u20131 to eventual runners-up Japan.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 June 2015 |title=Mizuho Sakaguchi sends Japan to quarterfinals in win over Netherlands |url=https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/06/24/japan-netherlands-womens-world-cup-results-mizuho-sakaguchi-goal-round-of-16 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands hosted and won the [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017|2017 European Championship]], earning their first major international title with a dominating style implemented by interim manager [[Sarina Wiegman]].<ref>{{cite news |date=6 August 2017 |title=Netherlands Women 4\u20132 Denmark Women |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40825848 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ramesh |first=Priya |date=7 August 2017 |title=Holland victory a triumph for Dutch flair and Sarina Wiegman's tactical nous |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2017/aug/07/holland-womens-football-euro-2017-sarina-wiegman |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Dutch earned the last remaining European berth in the 2019 Women's World Cup by finishing second to Norway in its [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 3|qualification group]] and winning the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA play-offs|play-offs]], defeating [[Denmark women's national football team|Denmark]] over two legs in the semi-finals and [[Switzerland women's national football team|Switzerland]] in the finals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Profile: The Netherlands |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/teams/team/1884883/profile/ |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=13 November 2018 |title=Dutch claim last European ticket for France 2019 |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/dutch-claim-last-european-ticket-for-france-2019 |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Dutch, ranked eighth in the FIFA World Rankings,<ref name=\"ranking\"/> were drawn into [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Group E|Group E]] with two of their 2015 group stage opponents, Canada and [[New Zealand women's national football team|New Zealand]], alongside [[Cameroon women's national football team|Cameroon]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=8 December 2018 |title=Some familiar faces await Canada at 2019 Women's World Cup in France |url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/sports-pmn/canada-to-meet-the-netherlands-new-zealand-and-cameroon-at-womens-world-cup |work=[[The National Post]] |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> Their opening match against New Zealand was scoreless until a last-minute header by substitute [[Jill Roord]] in stoppage time won it 1\u20130 for the Dutch.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pender |first=Kieran |date=11 June 2019 |title=Netherlands' Jill Roord pounces at the last to break New Zealand hearts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jun/11/new-zealand-netherlands-womens-world-cup-match-report |work=The Guardian |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands secured a knockout stage berth by defeating Cameroon 3\u20131 on the second matchday, with two goals by [[Vivianne Miedema]] to make her the nation's all-time top goalscorer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Poole |first=Harry |date=15 June 2019 |title=Women's World Cup: Netherlands beat Cameroon 3\u20131 to reach last 16 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48641765 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Dutch finished with a three-win record and topped the group after winning 2\u20131 against Canada. An early penalty was rescinded by the VAR and the opening goal was scored by Dutch defender [[Anouk Dekker]] in the 54th minute. [[Christine Sinclair]] scored an equaliser six minutes later, but the Netherlands restored their lead in the 75th minute through a short-range finish by substitute [[Lineth Beerensteyn]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davidson |first=Neil |date=20 June 2019 |title=Christine Sinclair scores goal No. 182 but Canada loses to Dutch at World Cup |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2019/06/20/canada-captain-christine-sinclair-scores-goal-no-182-against-dutch-at-world-cup.html |work=[[Toronto Star]] |agency=The Canadian Press |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe round of 16 fixture for the Oranje was also a rematch against Japan, which manager Wiegman expected to end with a different result.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Jamie |date=21 June 2019 |title=Netherlands relishing Japan rematch at Women's World Cup |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/football/netherlands-relishing-japan-rematch-womens-world-cup/article28099375.ece |work=[[Sportstar]] |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> [[Lieke Martens]] scored in the 17th minute with a backheel flick off a corner kick, but Japanese midfielder [[Yui Hasegawa]] equalised before half-time. The second half saw Japan creating more chances, with Dutch goalkeeper [[Sari van Veenendaal]] crucially saving a shot from [[Yuka Momiki]] in the 80th minute to keep the scores level.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/finalists-keepers-in-focus |title=Finalists' keepers in focus |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=5 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> In second-half stoppage time, the Dutch were awarded a controversial penalty kick by the VAR for a handball in the box by captain [[Saki Kumagai]], which was then scored by Martens to win the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |last=McElwee |first=Molly |date=25 June 2019 |title=Japan devastated as late handball gifts Holland penalty to secure World Cup quarter-final place |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2019/06/25/holland-vs-japan-womens-world-cup-last-16-live-score-latest/ |work=The Telegraph |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands defeated [[Italy women's national football team|Italy]] 2\u20130 in the quarter-finals, also qualifying for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2020 Olympics]], through second-half headers scored by Miedema in the 70th minute and [[Stefanie van der Gragt]] ten minutes later.<ref>{{cite news |last=Begley |first=Emily |date=29 June 2019 |title=Women's World Cup: Netherlands beat Italy 2\u20130 to reach first semi-final |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48777144 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The match was played in {{convert|34|C|F}} heat and required several cooling breaks, which slowed the tempo of play.<ref>{{cite news |last=McElwee |first=Molly |date=29 June 2019 |title=Holland reach first ever Women's World Cup semi-final with two headed goals against Italy |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2019/06/29/italy-vs-holland-womens-world-cup-2019-live-score-latest-updates/ |work=The Telegraph |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Netherlands reached their first Women's World Cup final by winning 1\u20130 in [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] against Sweden in the semi-finals. The match was scoreless in regulation time, due to the performances of both defences and goalkeepers, who made saves to keep several chances from breaking the deadlock. [[Jackie Groenen]] scored the lone goal of the match in the 99th minute, striking from {{convert|20|yd|m}} to beat goalkeeper [[Hedvig Lindahl]], with her first shot on target during the tournament.<ref>{{cite news |last=Edwards |first=Luke |date=3 July 2019 |title=Jackie Groenen hits extra-time winner to send Holland to World Cup final |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/world-cup/2019/07/03/holland-vs-sweden-womens-world-cup-semi-final-live-score-latest/ |work=The Telegraph |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=3 July 2019 |title=Judo ace Groenen throws Dutch towards unlikely World Cup glory |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/judo-ace-groenen-throws-dutch-towards-unlikely-world-001308465--sow.html |work=Yahoo Sports |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The Dutch were the third reigning European champions to reach the final, following Germany in 2003 and 2007, and the first to play a non-European country in the final.<ref name=\"UEFA\">{{cite news |date=3 July 2019 |title=Netherlands face US in Women's World Cup final |url=https://www.uefa.com/womensworldcup/news/newsid=2586627.html |work=UEFA.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> The Netherlands also managed to reach the final without trailing in their six victories, conceding only once in the knockout stage but not leading at half-time in any of their matches.<ref>{{cite news |date=5 July 2019 |title=The Women's World Cup is drawing record audiences |url=https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2019/07/05/the-womens-world-cup-is-drawing-record-audiences |work=[[The Economist]] |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/82863/late-again-the-dutch-still-like-their-chances.html |title=Late again, the Dutch like their chances even if media back home don't |website=[[Soccer America]] |date=5 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe success of the Dutch side has brought national attention to the women's football program, including thousands of fans who travelled to France to attend matches and record television ratings reaching 5 million viewers for the semi-final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lewis |first=Aimee |date=6 July 2019 |title=USA vs. Netherlands: Dutch World Cup success was decades in the making |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/06/football/netherlands-usa-womens-world-cup-final-spt-intl/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lyall |first=Sarah |date=24 June 2019 |title=Painting the Town Orange: A Day Out With the Dutch at the World Cup |page=B11 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/24/sports/painting-the-town-orange-a-day-out-with-the-dutch-at-the-world-cup.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Pre-match==\n\n===Scheduling===\nThe final's scheduling on 7 July led to a degree of criticism among supporters of women's football, as two continental men's tournament finals were held on the same day\u2014the [[2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica Final|Copa Am\u00e9rica]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] and the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup Final|CONCACAF Gold Cup]] in [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/a46a6df365134d8b8f8719772cbcdcc6 |title=Women's soccer: Wait and see approach to FIFA strategy |first=Anne M. |last=Peterson |agency=Associated Press |date=11 October 2018 |access-date=25 May 2019}}</ref> The latter final also featured the [[United States men's national soccer team|men's team of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |location=[[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2019/07/04/christian-pulisic-usa-defeat-jamaica-reach-gold-cup-final/1644682001/ |title=US defeats Jamaica to reach Gold Cup final against old foe Mexico |website=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=4 July 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> However, FIFA confirmed the Women's World Cup dates in September 2017, prior to the dates announced by [[CONMEBOL]] and [[CONCACAF]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/who-we-are/news/oc-for-fifa-competitions-approves-procedures-for-the-final-draw-of-the-2907924 |title=OC for FIFA Competitions approves procedures for the Final Draw of the 2018 FIFA World Cup |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=14 September 2017 |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhile FIFA called the scheduling a \"rare and exciting occurrence\", U.S. co-captain Megan Rapinoe criticised it as \"ridiculous and disappointing\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Blum |first=Ronald |date=4 July 2019 |title=The final insult: Women's World Cup final forced to compete with Copa America, CONCACAF |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/soccer/the-final-insult-women-compete-with-copa-america-concacaf/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref> CONCACAF president [[Victor Montagliani]] said that the scheduling of the Gold Cup final had been the result of a \"clerical error\" and that the conflict was not realised until it was too late.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Rory |date=6 June 2019 |title=Women's Soccer's Big Moment, Big-Footed by Indifference and a 'Clerical Error' |page=B7 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/07/sports/womens-world-cup-preview.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Match ball===\n[[File:2019 Women's World Cup Ball.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|Tricolore 19, the match ball of the final.]]\n\nThe official match ball for the final was the [[Adidas]] Tricolore 19, introduced for the knockout stage as a red-coloured variant of the Conext 19. The ball featured a blue-and-red glitch graphic, and pays homage to the original [[Adidas Tricolore]], which was introduced for the men's [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], in which France were victorious for the first time while on home soil.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/official-ball-for-france-2019-knockout-phase-unveiled |title=Official ball for France 2019 Knockout phase unveiled |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=21 June 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Officials===\n[[File:2017293155419 2017-10-20 Fussball Frauen Deutschland vs Island - Sven - 1D X MK II - 0017 - B70I0638.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|[[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]], the referee for the final.]]\n\nOn 5 July 2019, FIFA named French official [[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]] as the referee for the final.<ref name=\"referee\">{{cite news |date=6 July 2019 |title=Frappart: Final role a huge source of pride |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/frappart-final-role-a-huge-sense-of-pride |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=6 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706143910/https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/frappart-final-role-a-huge-sense-of-pride |archivedate=6 July 2019}}</ref> Frappart had been a [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA referee]] since 2009,<ref>{{cite web |title=Referees: France |url=https://www.fifa.com/development/education-and-technical/referees/association=fra/index.html |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=5 July 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707083706/https://www.fifa.com/development/education-and-technical/referees/association=fra/index.html |archive-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> and previously officiated at the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]], [[Football at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]] and [[UEFA Women's Euro 2017]].<ref>{{cite news |date=12 March 2018 |title=St\u00e9phanie Frappart retenue parmi les arbitres |language=French |trans-title=St\u00e9phanie Frappart among selected referees |url=https://www.eurosport.fr/football/coupe-du-monde-feminine/2019/stephanie-frappart-retenue-parmi-les-arbitres_sto7037659/story.shtml |publisher=[[Eurosport]] |agency=Agence France-Presse |access-date=6 July 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, she became the first woman to referee in [[Ligue 1]], the top men's professional league in France.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/french-ligue-1/story/3837476/stephanie-frappart-becomes-first-woman-to-referee-ligue-1-match |title=Ligue of her own: Female ref makes historic debut |website=ESPN |date=28 April 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> The final was Frappart's fourth match as referee during the tournament, having officiated two group stage matches and a quarter-final fixture. Her compatriot Manuela Nicolosi was chosen as one of the assistant referees, along with Irish official Michelle O'Neill. [[Claudia Umpi\u00e9rrez]] of Uruguay was chosen as the fourth official, with her compatriot Luciana Mascara\u00f1a serving as the reserve assistant referee. Spaniard [[Carlos del Cerro Grande]] was named the [[video assistant referee]], presiding over the first use of the technology in the final of the Women's World Cup. His fellow countryman [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda S\u00e1nchez Mart\u00ednez]] was named as one of the assistant video assistant referees for the match, along with Mariana de Almeida of Argentina.<ref name=\"USA-NED line-ups\"/>\n\n===Team selection===\nAmerican co-captain Megan Rapinoe, who scored five goals and had three assists during the tournament, was left out of the semi-final line-up against England due to a [[pulled hamstring]]. However, she said that she expected to return ahead of the final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hays |first=Graham |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3891501/rapinoe-hammy-expects-to-be-fit-for-the-final |title=Rapinoe (hammy) expects to be 'fit for the final' |website=ESPN |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref> U.S. midfielder Rose Lavelle also had to be substituted out in the semi-final due to a hamstring injury,<ref>{{cite news |last=Killion |first=Ann |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/annkillion/article/One-more-game-for-U-S-women-who-will-play-for-14067772.php |title=One more game for U.S. women, who will play for World Cup title |website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=2 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref> though she also said that she was fit to play in the final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bird |first=Hayden |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/soccer/2019/07/03/alex-morgan-tea-celebration-criticism-england |title=Morning sports update: Former England players were not happy with Alex Morgan's tea celebration |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=3 July 2019 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nDutch winger Lieke Martens, winner of [[The Best FIFA Women's Player]] in [[The Best FIFA Football Awards 2017|2017]], was also listed as questionable due to a toe injury. She started in the semi-final against Sweden, previously a doubt for the match, though she was unable to make an impact and was substituted out at half-time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Evans |first=Simon |location=[[Lyon]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-worldcup-nld-swe-martens/dutch-star-martens-hopes-to-make-final-despite-injury-idUSKCN1TY30C |title=Dutch star Martens hopes to make final despite injury |website=[[Reuters]] |date=3 July 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref> The team's goalkeeper, [[Sari van Veenendaal]], finished the semi-final with a swollen hand, but returned to the starting line-up for the final.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/news/usa-netherlands-key-strengths-and-areas-of-concern |title=USA\u2013Netherlands: Key strengths and areas of concern |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |date=5 July 2019 |access-date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=horizontal |total_width=300\n| image1 = Megan Rapinoe (May 2019) (cropped).jpg\n| alt1 = U.S. player Megan Rapinoe jogging towards the camera\n| image2 = Rose Lavelle (36648133634).jpg\n| alt2 = U.S. player Rose Lavelle waving to a member of the audience\n| footer = [[Megan Rapinoe]] (left) and [[Rose Lavelle]] (right) scored second-half goals for the United States in the final.\n}}\n\nThe United States fielded their unusual 4\u20133\u20133 that was used by Jill Ellis during the tournament, including Megan Rapinoe, the U.S. captain for the match, after her injury that kept her from starting in the semi-final. Lieke Martens returned for the Netherlands side, while [[Shanice van de Sanden]] was placed on the bench.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bushnell |first=Henry |date=7 July 2019 |title=Megan Rapinoe returns to USWNT starting lineup for World Cup final |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/world-cup-final-starting-lineups-usa-netherlands-megan-rapinoe-2019-134645618.html |work=Yahoo Sports |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The match kicked off at 17:00 in {{convert|31|C|F}} heat, which was lower than the earlier forecasts for the ongoing [[June 2019 European heat wave|continental heat wave]].<ref name=\"NYT-Live\">{{cite news |last=Das |first=Andrew |date=7 July 2019 |title=U.S. Wins Record Fourth World Cup Title |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/07/sports/soccer/usa-vs-netherlands-score.html |work=The New York Times |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> The match was attended by 57,900 spectators, including a large number of American fans and a stand of Dutch fans organised behind one of the goals.<ref name=\"NYT-Live\"/> French president [[Emmanuel Macron]], Dutch monarch [[Willem-Alexander of the Netherlands|Willem-Alexander]], and several professional male and female footballers were also among those in attendance.<ref name=\"LAT-Summary\">{{cite news |last=Baxter |first=Kevin |date=7 July 2019 |title=Women's World Cup final: U.S. defeats Netherlands to win another title |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/soccer/la-sp-uswnt-netherlands-world-cup-score-updates-20190707-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe United States started several attacks early in the match, but failed to score within the opening twelve minutes as they had in their previous six matches. The two sides traded fouls, including one that earned [[Sherida Spitse]] a yellow card in the tenth minute, but the U.S. remained in control of possession and had several chances towards goal.<ref name=\"NYT-Live\"/><ref name=\"Guardian-Live\">{{cite news |last=Dure |first=Beau |date=7 July 2019 |title=USA beat Netherlands 2\u20130 to win Women's World Cup final \u2013 as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/jul/07/womens-world-cup-final-usa-netherlands-live |work=The Guardian |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> Dutch goalkeeper and captain [[Sari van Veenendaal]] made several saves to keep her shutout, including two shots before half-time from [[Sam Mewis]] and Alex Morgan. A foul on [[Rose Lavelle]] at the top of the penalty area was left uncalled, allowing the Dutch to spring a counterattack that ended with a foul on forward [[Lineth Beerensteyn]] by U.S. defender [[Abby Dahlkemper]], who earned a yellow card. In first half stoppage time, U.S. defender [[Kelley O'Hara]] and Dutch winger Lieke Martens collided heads during an aerial challenge, resulting in O'Hara being substituted at half-time for [[Ali Krieger]].<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/>\n\nAnother physical challenge, resulting in a bloody facial cut for U.S. defender [[Becky Sauerbrunn]], began the second half as the U.S. continued to have the majority of attacking chances. Dutch defender [[Stefanie van der Gragt]] kicked U.S. attacker Alex Morgan in the shoulder while attempting to control the ball in the penalty area, which was left uncalled until a VAR review by referee St\u00e9phanie Frappart awarded a penalty to the United States. Van der Gragt earned a yellow card and the penalty was scored in the 61st minute by U.S. captain Megan Rapinoe, who left Van Veenendaal standing on her line;<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |last=Wrack |first=Suzanne |date=7 July 2019 |title=Megan Rapinoe on the spot as USA beat Netherlands to win Women's World Cup |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jul/07/womens-world-cup-final-report-usa-netherlands |work=The Guardian |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> the penalty was Rapinoe's sixth goal of the tournament, winning her the Golden Boot and making her the oldest player to score in a Women's World Cup final.<ref name=\"WaPo\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |last2=Giambalvo |first2=Emily |date=7 July 2019 |title=U.S. wins Women's World Cup title with 2\u20130 defeat of Netherlands |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/07/07/uswnt-netherlands-world-cup-final/ |work=The Washington Post |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gonzalez |first=Roger |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/womens-world-cup-final-uswnts-megan-rapinoe-opens-the-scoring-makes-history-with-penalty-kick-goal/ |title=Women's World Cup final: USWNT's Megan Rapinoe opens the scoring, makes history with penalty kick goal |website=[[CBS Sports]] |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref> Eight minutes later, Rose Lavelle scored the second goal of the final for the U.S. on a solo run through the Dutch defence that ended with a left-footed strike from {{convert|17|yd|m}}.<ref name=\"WaPo\"/>\n\nDown 2\u20130 and still conceding attacking chances to the U.S., the Netherlands substituted defender [[Anouk Dekker]] for forward [[Shanice van de Sanden]] and forced a save out of U.S. goalkeeper [[Alyssa Naeher]]. Van Veenendaal made several saves to deny a third goal for the United States after shots on target by Morgan, [[Tobin Heath]], and [[Crystal Dunn]].<ref name=\"Guardian-Live\"/> Rapinoe was substituted by Christen Press in the 79th minute, while Carli Lloyd was brought on in the last minutes of regulation time. After the end of the match, the U.S. bench spilled onto the field to celebrate the team's fourth Women's World Cup title.<ref name=\"NYT-Live\"/><ref name=\"WaPo\"/>\n\n===Details===\n<section begin=Final />{{Football box\n|date={{Start date|2019|7|7|df=y}}\n|time=17:00 <noinclude>[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]</noinclude>\n|team1={{fbw-rt|USA}}\n|score={{score link|2019 FIFA Women's World Cup knockout stage#Final|2\u20130|2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final}}\n|report=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/matches<!--/round=278517-->/match/300438259/\n|team2={{fbw|NED}}\n|goals1=\n*[[Megan Rapinoe|Rapinoe]] {{goal|61|pen.}}\n*[[Rose Lavelle|Lavelle]] {{goal|69}}\n|goals2=\n|stadium=[[Parc Olympique Lyonnais]], [[D\u00e9cines-Charpieu]]\n|attendance=57,900<ref name=\"match report\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/eng-52-0707-usa-ned-fulltime-pdf-3044630.pdf?cloudid=owdlkbnw1p9sf7wnlhfs |title=Match report \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |format=PDF |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n|referee=[[St\u00e9phanie Frappart]] ([[French Football Federation|France]])\n}}<section end=Final />\n<section begin=Line-ups />\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _usa19hw\n |pattern_b  = _usa19hw\n |pattern_ra = _usa19hw\n |pattern_sh = _usa19hw\n |pattern_so = _usa19wh\n |leftarm    = FFFFFF\n |body       = FFFFFF\n |rightarm   = FFFFFF\n |shorts     = FFFFFF\n |socks      = FFFFFF\n |title      = {{nowrap|United States}}<ref name=\"USA-NED line-ups\">{{cite web |url=https://resources.fifa.com/image/upload/eng-52-0707-usa-ned-tacticalstartlist-pdf-3044546.pdf?cloudid=bnrme8aiv1jnynuvjkyx |title=Tactical Line-up \u2013 Final \u2013 USA v Netherlands |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration International